{We will start with discussing the general strategies in the Spanish, both
from the White and Black perspective, in order to give you a better
understanding of what you are supposed to do in the arising positions and what
to be mindful of. The main goal of this repertoire is to play on understanding
with less requirement of theoretical knowledge, but, where it's absolutely
best, I will recommend following the well-paved theoretical paths.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {After this sequence of moves, there are many lines that White
can choose to play, and this repertoire will be built on the ones who require
more understanding than theory, in this instance, when to play the move d2-d3.
I have seen many players who want to avoid theory but play the move d2-d3 in
the wrong circumstances, even when the setup that Black employs requires a
more energetic response from White. In general, a good thing to remember is:
When Black doesn't develop the knight on f6, there is no pressure on the
e4-pawn so White will push d4 or first prepare it with c3 and then d4!} *

