{This is a game that shows many ideas for both sides, especially the typical
Bg4 mistake. White was much better but later he should have kept the
dark-squared bishops in this instructive blitz game!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 {In general, a good rule to remember is that when Black doesn't play Nf6,
there is no pressure on the e4-pawn so White plays d4, otherwise if Nf6, White
plays with the pawn on d3.} Nf6 (3... a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 (4... d6 5. c3 Bd7 6. O-O
Nge7 (6... Nf6 7. Re1 g6 8. d3 {Since Black delayed the move Nf6, White also
had the option of playing d4, but d3 is also fine.}) 7. Re1 (7. d4 {Again,
this typical move is played especially when Black's knight isn't on f6.}) 7...
Ng6 8. d3 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nf1 f5 {Black managed to get f5 in with a
comfortable position.}) 5. O-O Nge7 6. d3 (6. c3 {White should prepare d4!})
6... O-O 7. c3 d6 8. Nbd2 f5 {Another example where Black reaches a
comfortable position because White didn't play energetically enough.}) (3... g6
4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 (5. c3 Nge7 6. d4 {There is no pressure on the e4-pawn, so
this is White's typical idea.}) 5... Nge7 6. d3 O-O 7. Nbd2 d6 8. c3 h6 9. Bc4
Kh7 10. a4 f5 {White played too slow in the opening and allowed Black a free
hand, instead, White should have gone d4! and to put pressure on the opponent.
Remember the rule when to play with or without d4!}) 4. d3 d6 {Quite often,
after defending the e5-pawn with d6, Black's idea can be a6-b5, and when the
bishop arrives on b3, Na5. So with that in mind, White's next move is logical:}
(4... Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nbd2 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 Na5 10. Bc2) 5. c3 {
Making the c2-square available for White's bishop.} (5. O-O {This is slightly
inaccurate as it doesn't pay attention to what is Black playing.} a6 6. Ba4 (6.
Bxc6+ bxc6 {Would be probably best for White with this move order, when the
position is around equal.}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 Na5 {And Black can capture the
light-squared bishop on b3 with a pleasant position.}) 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7.
Nbd2 (7. Bg5 {This isn't a good move when Black's bishop is on e7.}) (7. Re1 {
Also fits in White's plans of Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3, and also it has the role of
discouraging Black's d6-d5 pawn break.}) 7... Bg4 $2 {In general, this would
be a good move if White had the pawn on d4 instead of d3, so Black would be
putting pressure on it. In this case, Bg4 is a positional mistake and White
should play h3 right away.} (7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2) (7... Ne8 {As a
principle, Black might be threatening to play f7-f5, and that is a good pawn
break when White's d-pawn is on d3 or d5, but not on d4!} 8. d4 {Immediately
putting pressure on the e5-pawn, making f7-f5 unattractive.}) 8. h3 Bh5 $2 {
As they say, mistakes come in pairs - this is another mistake from Black.} ({
Black should realize his mistake with Bg4 and retreat with} 8... Bd7 {when
after} 9. Re1 {White got an extra move h2-h3 that is useful. Next is Nf1-Ng3
or Nf1-Ne3, when it's good to keep in mind that White can also sometimes start
playing on the queenside by pushing the a and b-pawns. As for the push d3-d4,
we would like to play only under good circumstances or if Black starts some
play on some flank.}) (8... Bxf3 9. Nxf3 {White immediately gained the upper
hand by this exchange as now White's light-squared bishop doesn't have an
opponent, and when the position opens up, the bishop's strength will increase
even more.}) 9. Re1 $16 {Intending Nf1-Ng3.} a6 10. Ba4 (10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nf1
{This is also an interesting continuation but I would like to preserve the
light-squared bishop.}) 10... b5 11. Bc2 $1 {When to play Bc2 and when to play
Bb3? When Black's dark-squared bishop is on e7 or g7, we would like to play
Bc2. If Black's bishop is on c5, then we should play Bb3 since the move Na5
will be meaningless, as after Na5 Bc2, Black won't have c7-c5.} (11. Bb3 Na5
12. Bc2 c5 {This is Black's idea, so White should have retreated to c2 right
away in this instance.}) 11... Nb8 {The so-called Breyer maneuver. A typical
idea for Black named after the Hungarian player Gyula Breyer.} 12. Nf1 Nbd7 13.
Ng3 (13. g4 Bg6 14. Ng3 {Playing in this style of g2-g4 included is mostly a
matter of taste, but in my opinion, once White already has an advantage,
weakening the king seems like an unnecessary risk, so I would prefer Ng3
without g4.}) 13... Bxf3 (13... Bg6 14. Nh4 Re8 15. Ngf5 {The computer usually
prefers this knight jump, with the intention of playing Qf3 and likely g2-g4
later on, but it seems unnatural to leave the knight on h4, especially when
our intention isn't to capture the bishop on g6. So you can take your pick of
which knight jump you prefer.} (15. Nhf5 {This is White's idea, establishing a
knight on the f5-square. If Black ever captures Bxf5, White would recapture
with the other knight.})) 14. Qxf3 $16 g6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Nf5 $2 {This is an
impressive-looking move but objectively it isn't good.} (16. d4 $18 {Pushing
d4 right away is also good.}) (16. b4 $1 $16 {This is a typical plan,
intending a2-a4 or improving the light-squared bishop by playing Bb3.} Bf8 (
16... c5 17. Bb3 {This is White's idea.}) 17. Bg5 h6 18. Bd2 Bg7 (18... a5 {
Now White has two options:} 19. a4 (19. a3 {Standing still on the queenside is
also fine.}) 19... axb4 20. cxb4 bxa4 21. Bxa4 Bg7 22. Bb3 {A natural move,
putting pressure on the f7-pawn.} (22. Bc6 {Is also possible.})) 19. a4 c6 20.
Bb3 $16) (16. Rad1 $1 {Intending d3-d4.} Bf8 17. Bc1 $1 $16 {Declining the
exchange and intending d4, when the dark-squared bishop doesn't stand in any
piece's way.} (17. Bg5 h6 18. Bc1 {Provoking h6 is also an interesting idea,
when now White can also consider pushing h2-h4-h5 or even f2-f4}) 17... Bg7 18.
d4 (18. b4 {This is another typical plan for White, intending Bb3, improving
the bishop, while taking the c5-square away from Black's knight.} a5 19. a3
axb4 20. axb4 {Is also an interesting continuation of the game can continue.})
(18. h4 $5 h5 {The knight on g3 is restricted but on the other hand, White got
the g5-square.} 19. Bg5 c6 20. d4 Qc7 21. Bb3 {When the knight from g3 can be
improved later on.})) 16... Bf8 {This move takes the sting out of Nf5 when
White is forced to exchange the dark-squared bishops now.} 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18.
Nh6+ Kg7 19. Ng4 {Remember that in typical positions similar to the one before
Nf5, if White is missing the dark-squared bishop and the bishops are not in
tandem, the light-squared bishop can be worse than a knight.} Nxg4 20. hxg4 Qg5
{Black isn't worse anymore, although White went on to win this game.} 21. g3
Nf6 22. Bd1 h5 23. gxh5 gxh5 24. Qe3 Qxe3 25. Rxe3 Ng4 (25... Rh8 26. a4 {
This can be an interesting idea for White.}) 26. Bxg4 hxg4 27. Kg2 f5 28. exf5
Rxf5 29. Re4 Rg5 30. Rh1 Rf8 31. Rh4 Kf6 32. Rexg4 Rxg4 33. Rxg4 c5 34. c4 bxc4
35. dxc4 Rb8 36. b3 a5 37. Kf3 a4 38. bxa4 Rb2 39. Ke4 Rxa2 40. Kd5 Rd2+ 41.
Kc6 Kf5 42. Rg8 Rd4 43. Kb5 Rd2 44. a5 e4 45. a6 Rb2+ 46. Kc6 Ke5 47. a7 Ra2
48. a8=Q Rxa8 49. Rxa8 Kd4 50. Kxd6 Kxc4 51. Rc8 e3 52. Rxc5+ Kd4 53. fxe3+
Kxe3 54. g4 Kf4 55. g5 Ke4 56. g6 Kf4 57. g7 Ke4 58. g8=Q Kd4 59. Qg4+ Kd3 60.
Rf5 Ke3 61. Rf3+ Ke2 62. Qg2+ Ke1 63. Rf1# 1-0

