1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
Bg4 $2 (8... b5 9. Bc2 {The right retreat square!}) 9. Nbd2 $5 (9. h3 {Is also
good.}) 9... Re8 10. Nf1 (10. h3 {I would have preferred this move, asking
Black to state their intention with the bishop.} Bh5 11. Nf1 b5 12. Bc2 d5 13.
Ng3 Bg6 14. exd5 Qxd5 {The e5-pawn was under attack, so Black needs to
recapture on d5 with the queen.} 15. Nh4 $14 {The move Bb3 should also be
considered, although it doesn't seem convincing for White after the exchanges
on the d3-square and then on the e5-square, so it's better to just play Nh4.})
10... b5 11. Bc2 {The preferred retreat.} (11. Bb3 Na5 12. Bc2 {This is also
possible in this case since the knight on a5 doesn't support the e5-pawn
anymore, so d6-d5 is harder to play.}) 11... d5 {After Black's d5 in the
Spanish or Italian, White has both options available and needs to choose
either to capture exd5 or to keep maneuvering! There is no general rule since
every time it depends on the exact characteristics of each position.} 12. Qe2
Bd6 13. h3 Bh5 14. Ng3 Bg6 15. Nh4 (15. Bg5 $1 {This move puts pressure on
Black's knight and center, tempting Black into making a decision.} dxe4 16.
dxe4 $16 {Both dxe4 and Nxe4 are normal recaptures and should be considered.
In this case, I prefer the pawn recapture.}) 15... d4 (15... Nxe4 $1 {Be aware
of this move! It should be always calculated, and now the position becomes
messy.} 16. Nxe4 (16. dxe4 Qxh4 17. exd5 {Is playable.}) 16... Qxh4 (16... dxe4
{This allows Nxg6 and White gains the upper hand.} 17. Nxg6 exd3 18. Bxd3 hxg6
19. Be4 Ne7 (19... Qd7 20. Qf3 $18) 20. Bxa8 Qxa8 21. a4 $16) 17. Bg5 Qh5 {
The position remains complex but it's simply better to not allow all of these
complications and play 15.Bg5.}) (15... dxe4 $2 16. dxe4 $16 Nxe4 $2 17. Bxe4
$18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 16. Nhf5 Bxf5 17. Nxf5 $16 dxc3 18. bxc3 Bc5 (18... b4 19.
Ba4 $18) 19. Qf3 (19. Bg5 $5) 19... Ne7 20. Nh6+ $18 Kf8 21. Bb3 gxh6 22. Qxf6
1-0

