{In this game Black gets a correct version of the Bg4 move and gets a very
pleasant game according to the theory.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
Nf6 (4... g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. c3 d6 7. d4 Bd7) 5. O-O (5. d3 {This is the move
chosen for this repertoire, avoiding all the heavy theoretical lines after 5.
0-0 but keeping all the Spanish ideas in play!}) 5... Be7 (5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5)
6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 (8. a4 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4 11. Qe3 Nxb3 12.
Qxb3 c6) 8... O-O 9. d4 (9. h3 {This position is a crossroad where Black can
choose which Spanish to play.} Na5 {The Chigorin Spanish.} (9... Nb8 {The
Breyer Spanish.}) (9... Bb7 {The Zaitsev Spanish.})) 9... Bg4 {Black is
putting a lot of pressure on White's center and is threatening Bxf3 when gxf3
will be necessary. In other words, White is asked to clarify the situation in
the center whether with dxe5 or d5. This system is playable for White but it's
a bit impractical.} (9... h6 {Just an example of what would happen if it's
White's move.} 10. h3 {The best option, preventing Bg4. The idea is to keep
the center solid and flexible, restricting Black's pieces and activity. White
wants to continue with the plan Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3 and simply to improve the
position, and then at some point to think about dxe5 or pushing d5 to make
progress.}) 10. Be3 {The bishop successfully defends the d4-pawn but is
misplaced.} (10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 Qc8 (11... c6 {Is another option for Black.})
12. b4 Nc4 {This is how the game can continue after 10.d5.}) 10... exd4 (10...
Nxe4 11. Bd5 {Is White's point.}) 11. cxd4 Na5 (11... d5 12. e5 Ne4 {Leads to
more theory.}) (11... Nxe4 12. Bd5 {The e4-pawn is still immune to capture.})
12. Bc2 c5 (12... Nc4 13. Bc1 c5 14. h3 {This move isn't good because after:}
Bxf3 15. Qxf3 cxd4 {It will take too much time for White to regain the d4-pawn
if he can regain it at all.}) 13. d5 (13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. e5 $6
Nd5 $17) (13. Nc3 Nc4 14. Bc1 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ne5 17. Qe3 b4 18.
Nd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 {Black has many options in this position and is already
better.}) (13. Nbd2 Nc6 14. d5 Ne5 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Nxf3+ (16... Nfd7 17.
Nd2 $5) (16... Nc4 $5) 17. Qxf3 Nd7 18. Rad1 Bf6 {When the position is
playable for both sides.} (18... Bg5 {Is also possible.})) (13. h3 Bxf3 14.
Qxf3 Nc4 15. Bc1 $2 {Saving the bishop isn't good in this case and Black gains
the advantage after:} cxd4 16. Qd3 Qb6 {When Black can follow-up with Rac8 or
even d6-d5 can be considered.}) 13... Nc4 14. Bc1 (14. b3 $2 Nxe3 15. Rxe3 Nd7
16. Nbd2 Bf6 17. Rc1 Bg5 {And White is in trouble.}) 14... Nd7 {Black has a
very nice version of the Benoni.} 15. h3 (15. Nbd2 Nxd2 16. Bxd2 Ne5 (16... Bf6
$5) 17. Bc3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Ng6 $1 {Taking control over the dark squares.}) 15...
Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Bg5 (16... Bf6 $5 17. Nc3 g6 $5 (17... Re8 $5)) 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18.
b3 Nde5 19. Qf5 (19. Qe2 Nb6 20. Qe3 Qxe3 21. Rxe3 Rfe8 22. f4 Ng6 {White is
facing some issues since the f4-pawn is under attack while Nxd5 is threatened
at the same time.}) 19... Qxf5 20. exf5 Nb6 21. f6 gxf6 22. Nc3 Rad8 23. Rad1
Kg7 24. Ne4 Ng6 25. Ng3 Nf4 26. Nf5+ Kh8 27. Re4 Nbxd5 28. Rd2 Rg8 29. Kf1 Rg5
30. Nxd6 Rxd6 31. Rxf4 Ne3+ 32. Ke2 Rxd2+ 33. Kxd2 Nxc2 34. Kxc2 Rxg2 35. Rxf6
Kg7 36. Rf3 Kg6 37. a4 f5 38. Kd2 Kf6 39. axb5 axb5 40. Ke2 Rg7 41. Rd3 Ke5 42.
Re3+ Kd5 43. Rf3 Rf7 44. Rf4 Ke5 45. Rf3 f4 46. Rd3 Ra7 47. Rd8 Ra2+ 0-1

