{Here we will see a very instructive game by Carlsen in the Spanish with a
well-timed Bg4 move!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3
d6 7. c3 O-O 8. Nbd2 Re8 9. Re1 Bf8 10. Nf1 h6 {Prevents Bg5.} (10... g6 11.
Bg5 {Now this is a good moment to play Bg5 since Black's bishop isn't on e7,
and in general, White's plan can be to play Ne3 and expand on the queenside
with b4, Bb3, and then a4.} h6 12. Bh4 Bg7 13. Ne3 b5 14. Bc2 Nb8 15. a4 Bb7
16. b4 Nbd7 17. Bb3 {White enjoys a pleasant position and is in control.}) 11.
Ng3 (11. d4 b5 12. Bc2 Bg4 13. d5 Na5 14. Ng3 c5 (14... c6 $1 $11) 15. h3 Bd7
16. b3 {White is enjoying a pleasant advantage.}) (11. Ne3 g6 12. Bd2 Bg7 13.
b4 {Expanding on the queenside is still a good plan for White.}) 11... b5 12.
Bb3 {This move makes sense with the point that it discourages d6-d5, as after
the knight goes to a5, the e5-pawn would become more vulnerable.} (12. Bc2 {
The preferred retreat.} d5 13. a4 Bb7 {White has the luxury to choose when to
capture on b5 since ...bxa4 isn't good for Black, but also White can choose
when and whether to capture on d5. On top of that, White can always play the
sequence axb5 and then Rxa8, distracting either the queen or the bishop to the
a8-square.}) 12... Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. d4 (14. h3 g6 15. d4 exd4 16. cxd4 cxd4
17. Nxd4 Bb7 $13) 14... exd4 $3 {When White pushes d4 in a position such as
this one, Black has 3 ways to meet it - to ignore it with a move like Qc7, to
capture twice, or to capture once and play Bg4, a perfect reaction by Carlsen.}
15. cxd4 Bg4 $1 16. d5 (16. dxc5 dxc5 $15 {Keep in mind that we would like to
avoid dxc5 and this pawn structure in the Spanish as Black is usually slightly
better.} 17. h3 Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nc6 20. Be3 Nb4 $15) (16. h3 Bxf3
17. Qxf3 cxd4 18. Nf5 Rc8 $15) 16... Nc4 $1 {Jumping on c4 before White has
the time to play b3. Now Black has a wonderful version of the Benoni!} (16...
g6 $6 {Allows} 17. b3 {A very strong positional idea, restricting the knight
on a5.} Bg7 18. Rb1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 {It's good to note that White doesn't want
to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bb2.} (19. Qxf3 Nxd5 {White loses a
pawn, so the queen capture is impossible.}) 19... c4 20. Bf4 {Be aware that
even in a scenario like this when c3 is allowed} (20. b4 $5) 20... c3 {White
is doing very well in this position and can choose to continue with different
moves such as Qc1, Kh1, or Qd3, with a pleasant advantage.}) 17. h3 Bxf3 18.
gxf3 Nd7 (18... g6 19. b3 Nb6 $132) 19. b3 Ncb6 20. Kh2 g6 21. Rb1 Qh4 22. Be3
Bg7 23. f4 Rac8 24. Rg1 Kh8 25. Qf3 c4 26. b4 (26. Rbd1 cxb3 $1 (26... c3 $2
27. Rg2 {White has a big advantage.}) 27. Bxb3 Nc4 $1 $13) 26... c3 $1 27. e5
dxe5 28. f5 e4 $1 29. Nxe4 Ne5 30. Qg2 Nxd5 31. Nd6 Nxe3 32. fxe3 Rcd8 33. Rbd1
(33. Nxe8 Rd2 $19) 33... Rf8 34. fxg6 fxg6 35. Rgf1 Rxf1 36. Qxf1 Ng4+ 0-1

