{In this game we can observe the c5-c4 push by Black on bad terms - meaning
that White's knight was still on b1 protecting the c3-pawn, so b2-b4 was
possible! As a result, Black ended up with a very passive knight on b7.} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9.
h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 {The best move for White.} c4 $2 (12... Bd7
$1 {Black shouldn't rush with c4, and this seems to be the best move in the
position.} 13. b3 (13. Nbd2 $6 {This is an inaccurate move as it allows c5-c4
since after which b2-b4 isn't possible because of en passant when the c3-pawn
is loose.} c4 14. Nf1 Nb7 15. Ng3 Nc5 {The position remains playable of course,
but Black managed to reroute the knight and get some space on the queenside,
so it's around balanced.}) (13. a4 $2 {This is a big and very typical mistake!
White is playing on the wrong side of the board with a4. It's weaking some
squares on the queenside, so as a rule in general: if you are not absolutely
sure about the value of an a2-a4 move in the Spanish, it's better to avoid it
with White!} c4 $17 14. Nbd2 Nb7 15. Nf1 Nc5 16. axb5 (16. a5 Nb7 {White can't
play a5 as now Black will pick up the a5-pawn.}) 16... axb5 {And Black's
counterplay on the queenside arrives first.}) 13... Nb7 $1 14. Nbd2 Ne8 15. Nf1
g6 16. Bh6 Ng7 17. Ng3 {With a pleasant position for White.}) 13. b4 $1 {
This is the reason why c5-c4 isn't good in a scenario where the White knight
is still on b1, defending the c3-pawn.} cxb3 (13... Nb7 {Now, the knight on b7
is restricted and White should act quickly.} 14. a4 Bd7 15. Be3 Rfb8 16. a5 {
Even a move like this is good, blocking the queenside and then switching the
focus to the kingside. Some example lines of how the game can develop:} (16.
Nbd2 {Is also much better for White.}) 16... Nd8 (16... Rf8 17. Nbd2 Ne8 18. g4
g6 19. Nf1 {With Ng3 next when White has a big advantage.}) 17. Nbd2 Ne8 18. g4
g6 19. Nf1 Ng7 20. Ng3 f6 21. Kh2 Nf7 22. Rg1 Rf8 23. Qd2 Kh8 24. Rg2 Rg8 25.
Rag1 {The possibility to build up on the kingside thanks to the space
advantage makes White's position much more comfortable and with a sizeable
advantage.}) 14. axb3 Bd7 15. Be3 (15. Kh1 {This is just an example to give
the move to Black.} Nb7 {If Black manages to get Nb7-Nc5 in, Black is doing
fine because in that case b3-b4 can be met with Na4.} 16. b4 {It's good to
prevent Nc5.} (16. Bd2 Nc5 17. b4 Na4 {And Black is doing fine.}) 16... a5 17.
Bd2 axb4 (17... a4 18. Na3 {White's knight is doing very well on a3 and Bd3
can be next, targeting the b5-pawn, with a very pleasant position.}) 18. Rxa8
Rxa8 19. cxb4 Ra1 20. Qc1 {Even in scenarios where Black manages to infiltrate
on the queenside, White should keep his cool and slowly chase Black away from
White's camp, and the position is quite comfortable in general.}) 15... Nb7 16.
b4 $1 {Of course, restricting the knight immediately. All of Black's minor
pieces are passive.} a5 (16... Rfc8 17. Bd3 Nd8 18. Qb3 {White will soon
prepare c3-c4.} g6 19. Rc1 Nh5 20. Nbd2 f6 21. c4 {Opening up the queenside
where Black has weaknesses.}) 17. Bd3 $1 {The pawn should remain on b4!} axb4 (
17... a4 18. Qd2 $1 Rfc8 19. Rc1 Rab8 20. Na3 Nd8 21. c4 bxc4 22. Nxc4 Qb7 23.
Na5 Qa8 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. b5 Nb7 26. Nc6 $16) 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxb4 {With the
knight restricted on b7, the position is strategically winning for White.} Nd8
(19... Ra1 20. Qb3 Ne8 21. Nc3 Rxe1+ 22. Nxe1 Qc8 23. Nc2 (23. Nxb5 $18) 23...
Nc7 24. Na3 Qe8 25. Qc2 (25. Bb6 $5) 25... Nd8 26. Qe2 g6 27. Naxb5 $18) 20.
Qe2 Qb7 21. Nc3 Ra3 (21... Rb8 22. Nd2 {Rerouting the f3-knight via d2 and b3
to the a5-square is a typical idea.} Ne8 23. Nb3 Nc7 24. Na5 Qc8 25. Rc1 {
Black's pieces are tied up and White has a lot of pressure in the position.})
22. Qb2 $1 (22. Nxb5 $6 Rxd3 $1) 22... Ra8 23. Nd2 $1 Ne8 24. Nb3 f6 25. Na5
Qb8 26. Qe2 Nc7 27. Rc1 Nf7 (27... Nb7 28. Nc6 Bxc6 29. dxc6 Nd8 30. Nxb5 $18)
28. Nb1 $2 (28. Nc6 $1 $18 Bxc6 29. dxc6 Nd8 30. Nxb5 $18) 28... g6 29. Na3 f5
30. f3 Bg5 31. Bxg5 Nxg5 32. Qc2 Qb6+ 33. Qf2 Qxf2+ 34. Kxf2 Ra7 35. h4 Nf7 36.
Ke3 f4+ 37. Kd2 Kf8 38. Kc3 Ke7 39. Kb3 Nd8 40. Kc3 h6 41. Nb1 Na6 42. Kb3 Rc7
43. Nc3 Nb7 44. Ra1 Nbc5+ 45. bxc5 Nxc5+ 46. Kc2 b4 47. Nb5 b3+ 48. Nxb3 Bxb5
49. Bxb5 Nxe4+ 50. Bc6 Nf6 51. Kd3 g5 52. hxg5 hxg5 53. Ra8 Kf7 54. Nd2 g4 55.
Nc4 e4+ 56. fxe4 f3 57. gxf3 gxf3 58. Nxd6+ 1-0

