695,982,992]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 g6 7. h3
Bg7 8. Be3 {This is an interesting sub-system for White.} Bd7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10.
O-O Re8 11. Re1 {White's idea in this position isn't to play Nf1-Ng3 since
Black played g6 early on and Bg7, but instead White should focus on the
queenside.} Qe7 (11... Nh5 12. d4 Nf4 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Bc2 h6 15. b4 Qe7 16.
a4 g5 17. Nc4 {With a comfortable position for White.}) 12. b4 (12. d4 {
This move also makes sense since Black's queen is on e7, but our plan in
general is to push b2-b4.} exd4 13. cxd4 Nxe4 14. Bg5 Nxg5 15. Rxe7 Nxf3+ 16.
Nxf3 Rxe7 17. d5 $16) (12. a3 b5 13. Bc2 a5 14. a4 b4 15. Bb3 (15. Nc4 $5)
15... h6 16. Bc4 Nh5 17. d4 $14) 12... h6 (12... b5 $1 13. Bb3 a5 14. a3 Nh5
15. Qc2 {The position is playable for both sides, although White is slightly
preferable.}) 13. Bb3 Be6 (13... Nh5 {This points out that Black intends to
move the king and push f7-f5. White's plan was to push a4, but seeing that
Black might prepare f5, remember that f5 can be good when White's d-pawn is on
d3 or d5, but not when it's on d4! As the position will be complicated, it
should be calculated of course.} 14. a3 (14. d4 $5 exd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4
$14) 14... Kh7 15. d4 $1 exd4 16. cxd4 $16 (16. Nxd4 $5 {Capturing with the
knight in many cases is also possible.})) (13... b5 14. a4 $14) 14. a4 b6 15.
Bc2 Nh5 16. d4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Bd7 18. Nf5 gxf5 19. Qxh5 f4 20. Bxf4 Qf6 21. Be3
Qxc3 22. Bb3 Qf6 23. Rac1 Rac8 24. b5 axb5 25. axb5 Ne5 26. Qe2 Be6 27. Bxe6
