{White illustrates quite well how the game should be conducted in the Spanish
while playing on the queenside.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
d6 6. c3 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 b5 10. Bc2 Re8 11. a4 (11. Nf1 {
Once again, the knight doesn't belong on g3 in this case but it can make sense
to go to the e3 square, as White should focus on the queenside.} Bb7 (11... h6
12. Ne3 {Intending to continue on the queenside with a4 and b4.}) 12. Bg5 {
And then Ne3 next.} Nb8 13. a4 Nbd7 14. Ne3 h6 15. Bh4 {White has a pleasant
position overall, intending b2-b4 next.}) 11... Bb7 (11... b4 12. a5 {Quite
often this move should be kept in mind when Black plays b4, with the idea to
improve the light-squared bishop to a4.} (12. Nc4 {Is another possible
continuation, with a possibility of playing Bg5 and then later on Ne3.})) 12.
b4 d5 13. Nb3 {Black's dark-squared bishop is absent from the battle on the
queenside, so White immediately wants to make use of the weakened c5-square.}
dxe4 14. dxe4 Nd7 15. Qe2 (15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Be3 {Is also good, while 15.Be3 was
also possible.}) 15... bxa4 16. Rxa4 Qe7 17. Be3 Nb6 18. Raa1 Bc8 19. Nfd2 Rd8
20. Nc5 a5 21. Qb5 Na7 22. Qxa5 Nc6 23. Qxa8 Nxa8 24. Rxa8 Be6 25. Rea1 h5 26.
Nxe6 Qxe6 27. Bb3 Qe8 28. R8a6 Ne7 29. Nf3 Rd6 30. Ng5 Rxa6 31. Rxa6 Qc8 32.
Bxf7+ Kh8 33. b5 c6 34. Ra7 Bf6 35. b6 Bxg5 36. b7 Qg4 37. b8=Q+ Kh7 38. Bg8+
Kh6 39. Qf8# 1-0

