1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 g6 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. Nbd2 {
The early Bg5 often invites an h6-g5 from Black, so White players usually
postpone it and castle first, waiting for Black to castle too.} h6 9. Bh4 O-O
10. O-O Bd7 11. Re1 Re8 12. Nf1 (12. b4 {Is another way to go for White.})
12... Qc8 13. Ne3 Ne7 14. Bc2 {Protecting the pawn on e4 and making d3-d4 an
additional plan.} ({Not} 14. Bb3 {as it blocks the advance of the b-pawn, and
after all, Black can still play} Be6 {if he wants, insisting on the
light-squared bishop exchange.}) 14... Nh5 15. d4 Nc6 (15... exd4 16. Nxd4 {
This is my preferred capture in general, but cxd4 is also good.}) 16. Qd2 exd4
17. Nxd4 Ne5 18. Rad1 b5 19. Nd5 Kh7 20. Bb3 Rb8 21. Ne3 c5 22. Ne2 Bf8 23. f4
c4 24. Bc2 Ng4 25. Nxg4 Bxg4 26. h3 Bxe2 27. Rxe2 b4 28. cxb4 d5 29. Qxd5 Nxf4
30. Qxf7+ Bg7 31. Qxf4 1-0

