1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Black has many 3rd move alternatives but in
general, most of them aren't challenging in any way. Most often, we will
choose lines that are easy to play and lead to an advantage, however,
sometimes concrete theory will be required to be memorized in order to get the
maximum out of the position. Analysis of these lines can be found in the
theoretical chapter. One of the main things to remember is that the positions
can be different when Black first includes 3...a6 4.Ba4, because for the 3rd
move sidelines, if Black includes ...a6 later on, quite often White isn't
obliged to play Ba4 and has a better option in the position.} *

