1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {In this chapter, the theory of the 3rd move
alternatives will be examined. Our goal is always to avoid concrete theory as
much as possible and get a pleasant advantage with moves that are easy to
remember!} Nge7 $5 {This is an interesting sideline where it's good to note
that this isn't the same as 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nge7, as White isn't obliged to play
Ba4 after a6. Keep in mind the general strategies - Black isn't attacking the
e4-pawn with Nf6, so we want to play with d4 instead of d3.} (3... Nd4 $6 {
This isn't a very good move for Black, but it can have the point of surprising
us or getting us out of book, but White's play is quite easy after this move.}
4. Nxd4 exd4 5. O-O {We only need to remember the plans and ideas in this
position, but it's also good to note that this is the most accurate move to
start with. We intend to play d3 and Nd2 next, possibly even Qh5 if Black
develops his knight to e7, while f2-f4 also needs to be taken into account.}
Bc5 (5... c6 6. Bc4 {The better retreat than Ba4. This move puts more pressure
on Black and discourages d5.} Nf6 (6... d5 $2 {A big inaccuracy.} 7. exd5 cxd5
8. Re1+ Ne7 (8... Be7 9. Bb5+ Bd7 $4 10. Qg4 $3 $18 Bxb5 (10... g6 11. Qxd4 $18
) 11. Qxg7 $18) 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Na3 $16 {White also has other possible
alternatives such as:} (10. a4) (10. c4) 10... Bxb5 11. Nxb5 Qb6 12. c4 $3 dxc4
13. Na3 O-O-O 14. Nxc4 Qf6 15. d3 $16 Nc6 16. Qg4+ Kb8 17. Bg5 Qg6 18. Qg3+ Ka8
19. Bxd8 $18) (6... d6 7. d3 {With a very pleasant position.} (7. c3 {This is
also a playable move.} dxc3 8. Nxc3 {White has lead in development.} (8. dxc3 {
Isn't as good as capturing with the knight, but of course, it's also possible
as White's position is good in general.}))) 7. Re1 d6 8. d3 Be7 9. h3 O-O 10.
Nd2 $16 d5 {Isn't very good as Black will stay with a weak pawn on d4.} 11.
exd5 Nxd5 (11... cxd5 12. Bb3 Bc5 13. Nf3 {The d4-pawn is a target and White
can play Bf4 next. If the bishop on b3 ever feels too stuck, White can always
consider c3 if necessary.}) 12. Bxd5 cxd5 13. Nb3 Bf6 14. Bf4 a5 15. a4 $16 (
15. Be5 $16)) (5... a6 6. Bc4 {The bishop is more active on c4.}) 6. d3 $16 (6.
Qg4 Qf6 7. Qg3 c6 8. Bc4 $16) 6... c6 7. Bc4 d6 8. Qh5 Qe7 9. Bg5 Nf6 10. Qh4
$14) (3... Bc5 {This is a playable alternative for Black and it is a line that
requires a slight memorization. Again, as in other lines, it is different when
Black includes 3...a6 and 4.Ba4 first.} 4. c3 $1 Nf6 (4... Nge7 $6 {This move
would be playable for Black if ...a6 and Ba4 were included, but here White
gets a nice advantage.} 5. O-O $1 (5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ {Because of this
check, it's more accurate to start with 5.0-0.}) 5... a6 {Now it's a bit too
late for a6 as we don't need to go retreat with the bishop.} (5... O-O 6. d4
$16) 6. Bxc6 $1 {we see that black cannot just insert the move a6 whenever he
wants! It has to be done very early ...in order to force Ba4 ....otherwise
white will always consider after a6 the move Bxc6! gaining time to attack !}
Nxc6 7. d4 exd4 (7... Bd6 8. Bg5 f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2 $14) 8. cxd4 Be7 9. d5
Nb8 10. Nc3 d6 11. h3 O-O 12. Be3 $16) (4... f5 $6 {This move has been played
sometimes in this position but it seems a bit too optimistic.} 5. d4 $1 fxe4 (
5... exd4 $2 6. e5 $1 dxc3 7. Nxc3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Na4 Bb6 10. Nxb6 axb6 11.
a4 $1 d5 12. exd6 cxd6 13. Re1 $18) 6. Bxc6 $1 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. Qh5+ $1 g6
9. Qe2 $1 (9. Nxg6 $4 Nf6 10. Qh6 Rg8 11. Ne5 Rxg2 $36) 9... Bf5 10. Bf4 Nf6
11. Nd2 Qe7 (11... O-O 12. Bg5 $1 $16) 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Rae1 $1 $16 (13. f3 $1
exf3 14. Ndxf3 $14)) 5. d4 $1 (5. d3 {If you want, of course you can always
choose the slow strategical approach and play a long positional game, however,
objectively, d4! is much better than d3 in this position.}) 5... exd4 (5... Bb6
$6 6. Nxe5 $1 {By following the computer's first line, White gets an advantage
by force.} Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nxe4 8. Qg4 $1 Bxf2+ (8... Nxf2 $4 9. Qxg7 Rf8 10. Bg5
f6 11. exf6 Nxh1 12. f7+ $3 Rxf7 13. Qg8+ Rf8 14. Qe6+ Qe7 15. Qxe7#) (8... c6
9. Qxe4 cxb5 10. Bf4 O-O 11. O-O $16) 9. Ke2 Qh4 10. Qxg7 Rf8 11. Bh6 Bc5 12.
Nd2 $3 Qf2+ 13. Kd1 Nxd2 14. Bxd2 c6 (14... a6 15. Rf1 Qh4 16. Bg5 Qh5+ 17. Be2
Qg6 18. Qf6 $1 Qxf6 19. Bxf6 $16 d5 (19... d6 20. b4 Bb6 21. exd6 cxd6 22. Kc2
$18) 20. g4 $1 Be7 21. g5 $16) 15. Rf1 Qh4 16. Bd3 $16 d5 17. Kc2) 6. e5 Nd5 (
6... Ne4 $6 7. O-O $1 d5 8. exd6 $1 (8. cxd4 $5 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. h3 Bf5 11.
Be3 $14) 8... O-O 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. dxc7 Qxc7 11. cxd4 Bb6 12. Nc3 {With an
extra pawn, White's position is to be preferred.}) 7. O-O $1 {The most
accurate continuation. Now Black must know 7...Be7 to avoid falling into a
very tough position.} (7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 d6 $14) 7... Be7 $1 (
7... a6 $2 8. Ba4 Be7 9. cxd4 O-O 10. Bb3 Nb6 11. d5 Na5 12. d6 $18) (7... O-O
$2 8. cxd4 Be7 {Black won't be on time to play d6 because of:} 9. Qb3 $3 Nb6
10. d5 $1 Nb8 (10... Na5 11. Qc3 $18) 11. Nc3 d6 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Bg5 $1 f6
14. Be3 $16) 8. Nxd4 $1 {A rare but a very good move! White is at least
slightly better in all the lines.} O-O $1 (8... Nxe5 $4 9. Nf5 c6 10. Nxg7+ Kf8
11. Nh5 $18) (8... Nxd4 $6 9. Qxd4 c6 10. Bc4 Nb6 11. Bb3 O-O (11... d5 $4 12.
exd6 Qxd6 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14. Re1 $18) 12. Bf4 $16 {Preventing d5 or d6.}) 9. Nf3
$1 {I prefer this move over 9.Nf5.} (9. Nf5 $5 d6 10. Nxe7+ Ncxe7 11. exd6 Qxd6
12. Re1 Qg6 13. Bf1 Be6 14. Na3 Rad8 15. Qc2 $14 Qf6 (15... Bf5 $2 16. Qb3 b6
$4 17. c4 Nf6 18. Rxe7 $18) 16. Qd2 $1 c5 (16... h6 17. c4 Nb6 18. Qf4 $14) 17.
Qg5 $14) 9... Nb6 10. Bf4 $1 $14 {If Black pushes the d-pawn, White can
capture en passant and give Black an isolated pawn.} d5 (10... a6 11. Be2 d5
12. Qc2 $1 Bg4 13. Nbd2 Bh5 14. Bd3 Bg6 15. Rfe1 (15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rfe1 $16)
15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 $16 {These positions with the pawn on e5 and easy
development in the center are usually much better and easier to play for White!
}) (10... d6 11. exd6 $14) 11. Nbd2 $1 {This is the best after ...d5, but 11.
exd6 should also be known in case Black plays 10...d6 instead of 10...d5.} (11.
exd6 $5 Bxd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. Nbd2 $14 {White has a risk-free
advantage in the endgame.} Bg4 15. h3 (15. Rfe1 $14) 15... Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Rfe8
17. Rfd1 d5 18. Nd4 $14) 11... Bg4 12. Re1 Bh5 13. Nf1 (13. Qc2 $5 Bg6 14. Bd3
Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qd7 16. Rad1 $16) 13... a6 14. Bd3 $16) (3... f5 $5 {A playable
but very risky line for Black. It's mostly used as a surprised weapon.} 4. d3 {
After d3, quite often we want to capture exf5, with the point that Black won't
have e5-e4 anymore.} fxe4 $1 (4... d6 $6 5. exf5 Bxf5 (5... a6 6. Ba4 (6. Bxc6+
$5 bxc6 7. d4 e4 8. Ng5 Bxf5 9. Nc3 d5 10. f3 Nf6 11. O-O $14) 6... Bxf5 7. O-O
Nf6 8. d4 b5 9. Bb3 Be7 10. a4 $16 (10. c3 $16)) 6. d4 exd4 (6... e4 $2 7. d5
$18 exf3 8. dxc6 Qe7+ 9. Be3 O-O-O 10. Qxf3 $18) 7. O-O $16) (4... Nf6 $6 5.
exf5 $1 d6 (5... Ne7 6. Ba4 $1 $14 (6. Nxe5 c6 7. Ba4 Qa5+ $19)) (5... Bc5 6.
O-O O-O 7. Be3 $1 Qe7 (7... Nd4 8. c3 Nxb5 9. Bxc5 d6 10. Qb3+ $18) 8. Nc3 $16
Nd4 (8... d6 9. Bxc5 dxc5 10. Bxc6 $18) 9. Bc4+ Kh8 10. Re1 $18) 6. O-O Bxf5 7.
d4 e4 8. d5 $18) 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O {And now the main moves are 6...d6 and 6...
Bc5. In both cases, White has good chances for an advantage.} Bc5 (6... d6 7.
Bc4 $1 {A very good move and the latest fashion in this line.} (7. Nc3 $5 Be7
8. Be3 (8. Bc4 Na5 9. Be2 O-O $13) (8. Bg5 Be6 (8... O-O 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qd5+
Kh8 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 Bg4 13. Ne1 Rb8 14. Nd3 Bd7 15. Qc4 $16) 9. Qd3 O-O
10. Bc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4+ Kh8 12. Rad1 Nh5 13. Be3 Rxf3 $2 14. gxf3 Qd7 15. Qf7
$14) 8... O-O 9. Bc4+ Kh8 10. Ng5 Qe8 11. Ne6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6 Nd8 13. Bh3 c6 (
13... Qg6 14. Nb5 $16) 14. a4 Qg6 15. Qd3 $14) 7... Bg4 $1 (7... Be7 $2 8. Ng5
d5 9. exd5 Nd4 10. c3 $18) (7... Na5 $5 8. Be2 $1 Be7 (8... Nxe4 $4 9. Qd5 Nc5
10. b4 c6 11. Qd1 $18) (8... Be6 9. Nc3 {Black's pieces seem a bit
uncoordinated and White has some lead in development.} Be7 10. Ng5 Bg8 11. f4
$16) 9. b4 $1 Nc6 10. b5 Nb8 (10... Na5 11. Bd2 c6 12. Qe1 b6 13. Bxa5 bxa5 14.
bxc6 Qb6 15. Nc3 $18) 11. Ng5 $1 $16) 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 Qd7 $1 (9... Nd4 $2 10.
g4 Nxf3+ (10... Nxg4 $2 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. Nxe5 $3 Bxd1 13. Bf7+ Ke7 14. Nd5#)
11. Qxf3 Bg6 12. g5 $1 Nd7 (12... Nh5 13. Be6 $3 Qe7 14. Nd5 $18) 13. h4 $16 (
13. Qg4 $16)) 10. Nd5 O-O-O 11. Qd3 Kb8 12. a4 $1 Be7 (12... Nxd5 13. exd5 $1
Ne7 14. Ng5 h6 (14... Bg6 15. Qb3 $14) 15. Ne6 $16) (12... Ne7 13. Ng5 $3 Nexd5
(13... Bg6 14. Nxf6 gxf6 15. Nf7 Bxf7 16. Bxf7 $16) 14. exd5 c6 15. Be3 $1 $16)
13. c3 $5 Rhf8 14. Nd2 Bg6 15. b4 $16) 7. Nc3 {Simple and good.} (7. Qd3 $5 {
This is a nice line that is easy to learn. We would like to play Qc4 next.} d6
(7... O-O $4 8. Qc4+ $18) 8. Qc4 $1 {Preventing Black's 0-0.} Bd7 (8... Qe7 $2
9. Nc3 $5 (9. b4 $1 Be6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qa6 Bb6 12. a4 Nxe4 13. a5 Bxf2+ 14.
Rxf2 Nxf2 15. Qxc6+ Kf7 16. Kxf2 Rhf8 17. Kg1 Kg8 18. Be3 $16) 9... Be6 10. Nd5
$16) 9. Nc3 $1 (9. Bxc6 $5 Bxc6 10. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 11. Rxf2 dxe5 12. Nc3 Qe7 13.
Be3 Qf7 (13... O-O-O 14. Bxa7 $16) 14. Qxf7+ Kxf7 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Rad8 (
16... c6 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Rd1 $14) 17. c4 $14) 9... Qe7 $1 (9... a6 $2 10.
Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 12. Rxf2 dxe5 13. Bh6 $3 gxh6 14. Qe6+ Qe7 15. Rxf6
$18) 10. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 11. exd5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. a4 $1 a6 (13... O-O $4 14.
Bxd7 Qxd7 15. c3 Bc5 16. b4 Bb6 17. a5 $18) 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Be3 $1 Bxe3 16.
fxe3 O-O-O 17. b4 $1 Kb8 18. a5 $1 Rhf8 (18... Qb5 $2 19. Qxb5 axb5 20. Rf7 $18
) 19. Qb3 $14 (19. Qd3 $5 $14) 19... Qe7 20. b5 $16) (7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5 {
This is the main line where Black has some compensation of the pawn, but there
is also a lot of theory on this so I would recommend avoiding it.}) 7... O-O 8.
Bg5 d6 9. Nd5 $1 {White has a nice advantage in this position, especially
since Black's king is weak. Here are some sample lines:} Kh8 $1 (9... Ne7 $2
10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 Rf7 12. Bc4 d5 13. Bxd5 $3 Nxd5 14. exd5 Bg4 15. Qd3 $16
) (9... Be6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. c3 $1 Ne7 12. Bc4 Kh8 13. b4 c6 14. Ne3 $16 Bxe3
15. Bxe6 $16) 10. Nh4 $1 Nd4 11. Bc4 $1 b5 12. Bd3 c6 13. Nxf6 gxf6 14. Bd2 Rg8
15. Kh1 Bd7 (15... Be6 $2 16. c3 $18) 16. f4 $16) (3... g6 {This is a playable
but slightly risky move. Our strategy should be to play c3+d4, regardless of
whether we castle or not! It's good to note that the arising positions can be
reached via different move orders.} 4. c3 a6 $1 5. Ba4 Nge7 (5... Bg7 6. d4
exd4 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bc2 {Transposes.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 b5 (7... d5 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Bxc6+ $5 (9. O-O Bg7 10. Re1+ Be6 11. Bg5 Qd6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Ne4 Qb4
14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qc1 $1 $14 Rfe8 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. Nc5 $1 Bf5 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19.
h3 $14 (19. a4 $5 $14)) 9... bxc6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Bg5 Qd6 12. Re1+ Be6 13. Nbd2
{Transposes.}) (7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 b5 10. Bc2 d6 (10... d5 11. e5 $16)
11. Nc3 Na5 12. Bf4 $14 h6 (12... c5 $4 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bc7 $18
) 13. Re1 g5 14. Bh2 (14. Be3 Nc4 15. Bc1 $14) 14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5
Nxf5 17. Rc1 $14) 8. Bc2 $1 {I prefer this in comparison to Bb3 since Black
would eventually go Na5 and the bishop on b3 would be under attack.} Bg7 9. O-O
d6 $1 {Intending Bg4.} (9... O-O 10. h3 $5) 10. h3 $1 O-O 11. Nc3 $14 {White
is slightly better in these positions in general, but Black's counterplay
shouldn't be underestimated. Our goal is to exchange the dark-squared bishops
which can be accomplished by playing Be3/Bf4 and then Qd2/Qc1, intending Bh6.}
Bb7 (11... h6 12. Re1 Bb7 13. Ne2 $1 {Targeted against f7-f5.} (13. a3 $5 $16)
13... Qd7 14. Bd2 f5 15. d5 Ne5 16. Nf4 $18) (11... Na5 {Now White shouldn't
go Be3 due to Nc4.} 12. Bf4 Bb7 13. Re1 Qd7 14. Qc1 $5 f5 (14... Nc4 15. Bh6 {
This is possible immediately since capturing the bishop and then on b2 would
run into Ng5 and Qxh7.} (15. b3 Nb6 16. Bh6 {Is also fine for White with an
advantage.})) 15. Bh6 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Nf5 18. Qg5 $14) 12. Bf4 $1 (
12. Be3 $5 {This move is also good, just be mindful of Na5-Nc4, targeting the
bishop.} Na5 13. Qc1 $1 Nc4 $2 14. Bh6 $16 c5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. b3 Nb6 17. Qd2
$16 {White is almost winning.}) 12... Na5 13. Rc1 $14 (13. Qc1 $5 f5 14. Bh6
fxe4 15. Bxe4 $14)) (3... d6 $6 {This is too passive and not the same as 3...
a6 4.Ba4 d6. White gets at least a small advantage in all the cases after 3...
d6.} 4. d4 $1 {Black hasn't included ...a6 and Ba4, so he can't play b5 now.}
Bd7 (4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nf6 (6... Nxd4 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9.
Bf4 $16) 7. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 (7... Bxc6 8. Qd3 $16 Bd7 9. Bf4 $16) 8. Qf3 Be7 (8...
c5 9. Nf5 $16) 9. h3 O-O 10. O-O Rb8 11. b3 Re8 12. Bf4 (12. Bb2 $14) 12... Bf8
13. Bg5 $16 (13. Rad1 $14)) 5. Bxc6 $3 {Remember this wonderful move!} Bxc6 6.
Nc3 Nf6 (6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Qd3 (8. Qe2 $5 {This is also good but I
would prefer not to place the queen along the e-file.}) 8... Bd7 {White has
the center and the pieces are centralized, so it's better to aim for long
castling.} (8... Be7 9. Nf5 {Gives White a nice advantage.}) 9. Bf4 $1 (9. Be3
{Runs into} Ng4 $1 {Attacking the bishop.}) 9... Be7 {If Nh5 is played at any
moment, then the bishop can retreat to e3 and Black wouldn't have Ng4 anymore.}
10. O-O-O O-O 11. f3 {Intending g4.} c6 (11... Nh5 12. Be3 Bg5 13. Kb1 Bxe3 14.
Qxe3 Nf6 {We have reached an e4 vs d6 position where White has more space,
exchanged the dark-squared bishops, castled long and with active pieces, White
enjoys a big advantage.}) 12. Kb1 $16 (12. g4 $16)) 7. Qd3 $1 $16 (7. Qe2 $16 {
This is equally good and leads to similar play.}) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 (8...
Be7 9. Nf5 O-O 10. Bh6 Ne8 11. Bd2 $16) 9. Bf4 $1 Be7 (9... Nh5 10. Be3 $16) (
9... Ng4 10. Qd2 Be7 11. O-O-O $16) 10. O-O-O O-O 11. f3 c6 12. Kb1 b5 13. g4
b4 14. Nce2 d5 (14... a5 15. Nf5 $16) 15. e5 Ne8 16. h4 $16) ({This illogical
move has also been played in some games.} 3... Bb4 $2 4. c3 Ba5 5. Na3 Bb6 6.
Nc4 d6 7. O-O $16 (7. a4 $5 a6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. d4 $16)) 4. O-O $1 {When we
see Nge7 we will castle, and when we see Ng6 we should play d4! The same goes
for the variation with 3...a6 and 4.Ba4 included, but the theory is a bit
different, you can check the fourth move alternatives for Black.} Ng6 {This is
the main sideline that Black has from the 3rd move alternatives.} (4... d6 $6
5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 a6 (6... Bd7 7. Nc3 {With a pleasant position.}) 7. Be2 {
As previously mentioned, White isn't obliged to play Ba4 after ...a6.} Nxd4 8.
Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qd3 {The queen can go to any other square such as c3 or e3, but
it's good to note that we aren't afraid of moves such as Nb4 or Ne5 since they
misplace the knight.} Be7 10. Nc3 Ne5 11. Qd2 $1 {The dark-squared bishop from
c1 will be developed by b3 and Bb2.} (11. Qe3 O-O 12. Nd5 {White will capture
the bishop on e7 and get the bishop pair.}) 11... c6 {Prevents Nd5.} 12. b3 O-O
13. f4 Nd7 14. Bb2 Nc5 15. Bf3 $16) (4... a6 $6 5. Bc4 $1 {Our bishop is more
active on c4 and there may be Ng5 like an idea in the position.} Ng6 6. d4 exd4
7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Be3 {This is a good plan, but 8.Nf5 is also gives White a nice
advantage.} (8. Nf5 O-O 9. Qh5 $16 {Using the fact that Black didn't develop
the knight to f6.}) 8... Bxd4 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. a4 $1 {Prevents b5.
} (11. Nc3 b5 12. Be2 Bb7 13. Rad1 d6 {With the e4 and d6 pawn structure,
White has a slight edge.}) 11... Nf4 (11... d6 12. Nc3 Ne5 (12... Be6 13. Rad1
$4 {White can retreat the bishop, capture on e6, but just not this as it falls
under the following tactic:} c5 14. Qd3 Ne5 {and Black wins the bishop.}) 13.
Be2 {White can also retreat the bishop to another square, but this is good
enough.}) 12. Nc3 d6 13. g3 Ne6 (13... Nh3+ 14. Kh1 $16) 14. Qe3 $16) (4... g6
5. c3 $1 {In this line with ...g6, Black can throw in ...a6 at any moment and
it's very likely that it will transpose to the lines where ...a6 is played
earlier.} Bg7 (5... a6 6. Ba4 Bg7 7. d4 {Transposes to variations with ...a6
first.}) 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 d5 {Now White has two ways to deal with this line:}
(7... a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bc2 d6 10. h3 O-O 11. Nc3 {With a pleasant advantage.})
8. Bxc6+ $1 (8. e5 $5 Bg4 9. Bg5 (9. Nbd2 O-O 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 $16) 9...
Qd7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. h3 $16 (13. Qc2 $5 $16) 13...
Bxf3 14. Nxf3 c5 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Rc1 Qa5 17. a3 Rab8 (17... Rfd8 18. Nd4 $16)
18. Qd4 $14) 8... bxc6 (8... Nxc6 9. exd5 Ne7 {Capturing on d5 with the queen
would give White some initiative with moves like Nc3 and then d4-d5.} 10. Nc3
Nxd5 11. Bg5 f6 12. Re1+ Kf8 13. Bh4 $16) 9. e5 O-O 10. Re1 Bg4 11. Nbd2 Rb8
12. h3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 $16) 5. d4 $1 exd4 (5... Nxd4 $6 6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Qxd4 c6
8. Bc4 Qb6 9. Qc3 $1 (9. Be3 $1 {With a very comfortable advantage in the
endgame.} Qxd4 10. Bxd4 $16 b5 11. Bb3 $1 d6 (11... c5 {This move must be
calculated so we don't lose a piece, but here it works well for White thanks to
} 12. Bd5 {A good inbetween move.}) 12. Be3 {Stepping away from the c5 move
with tempo.}) 9... Qb4 10. Be3 Qxc3 11. Nxc3 d6 12. a4 $16 (12. f4 $16)) 6.
Nxd4 {White has a small but very comfortable advantage. The best move seems to
be 6...Bc5, but then we will soon get to a position with the strategy e4 vs d6
pawns without the dark-squared bishops, which is always better for White!} Bc5
(6... Nxd4 $6 7. Qxd4 {Transposes to the line with 5...Nxd4.}) (6... a6 7. Bc4
$16) (6... Be7 $6 7. Nf5 Bf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nd5 d6 10. c3 Bxf5 11. exf5 Nge5 12.
Qh5 $16) 7. Nf5 $1 (7. Be3 $5 $14 Nxd4 8. Bxd4 Bxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 d6 11.
Rfe1 Nf4 {Black is intending threats with Qg5.} 12. g3 Nh3+ {It's good to note
that White will stabilize the position and White isn't in any danger.} 13. Kg2
Ng5 14. f4 Bh3+ 15. Kf2 Ne6 16. Qe3 {When White still has a comfortable game.})
7... O-O 8. Be3 Bxe3 (8... Bb6 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nd5 $1 Bxe3 (10... Bxf5 11. exf5
Bxe3 12. fxg6 (12. fxe3 $5 Nge7 13. f6 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Ne5 15. fxg7 Kxg7 16. Qe4
f6 17. Bd3 Nxd3 18. cxd3 $16) 12... Bb6 13. gxf7+ Kh8 14. Qh5 $16 (14. Bd3 $5))
11. Ndxe3 $16) 9. Nxe3 $14 {White managed to accomplish the goal of exchanging
the dark-squared bishops, so this is a nice risk-free advantage for White
thanks to the extra space in the center. Here are some sample lines:} Re8 (9...
Nce7 10. Bc4 d6 11. Nc3 c6 12. Qd2 $16 (12. a4 {Is also good.}) 12... b5 13.
Bb3 a5 14. a4 b4 15. Ne2 $16) (9... Qg5 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bd3 $1 $16 (11. Bc4 $5
Qc5 12. Qd5 Qxd5 13. Ncxd5 b5 14. Bb3 Ra7 15. a4 b4 16. a5 {White has good
control and advantage in the position.} d6 17. Ra4 Bd7 18. Nxb4 Nd4 19. Ra3 Rb8
20. Nbd5 Nxb3 21. Rxb3 Rxb3 22. cxb3 Nf8 23. Rd1 Ne6 24. e5 Bb5 25. exd6 cxd6
26. Nc3 Be8 27. Rxd6 Kf8 28. b4 Ke7 29. Rb6 Kf6 30. f4 g6 31. Kf2 Kg7 32. f5
Nf4 33. f6+ Kh6 34. Kg3 g5 35. Nf5+ Kg6 36. Ne7+ Kh5 37. h4 h6 38. hxg5 hxg5
39. Rb8 {1-0 Tsolakidou,S-Navrotescu,A/Vrnjacka Banja SRB 2024}) 11... Nb4 12.
Ne2 $16 (12. Be2 $5 Nf4 13. a3 $16)) (9... d6 10. f4 $1 (10. Nc3 $5 Nce7 11.
Qd2 f5 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. exf5 Nxf5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Rad1 $13) 10... Nce7 11. f5
$1 Ne5 12. Nc3 c6 13. Be2 Qb6 (13... f6 14. Qd4 Qb6 {Now White has a typical
response:} 15. Qxb6 $1 axb6 16. a4 $1 $16) 14. Qd2 f6 15. Na4 Qc7 16. c4 Kh8
17. Rad1 Rd8 18. Nc3 $16) 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bc4 $16 (11. Bd3 Nf4 (11... d6 12. f4
$16) 12. Ncd5 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 d6 14. Rad1 $16) 11... d6 12. f4 $1 $16 {White is
in control and has a very comfortable advantage.} *

