[PlyCount "19"]
[EventDate "2025.01.21"]
[SourceVersionDate "2017.10.16"]

{In this lesson, the alternatives of 4...Nf6 will be discussed. In general,
with ...a6 and Ba4 included, we can compare the variations with the 3rd move
alternatives. In most, or even all cases, Black is better off by including a6,
having the extra possibility of going b7-b5 amongst other things. Perhaps the
only line that is better without ...a6 is 3...f5 in comparison to 3...a6 4.Ba4
f5. In general, when possible, I recommend playing the same way as we would on
the 3rd move alternatives, not necessarily getting the same positions but the
goal is so it can be easier to remember.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
Nge7 {This is an interesting and playable alternative for Black.} (4... f5 5.
d4 $1 {Dealing with this sideline energetically is the best approach! Black is
playing mainly for tricks, so it's good to know how to handle the position in
the opening. You can find how the game can continue in the theory chapter.}) (
4... d6 {This is another playable and interesting system for Black. It is
called Deffered Steinitz or Smyslov Spanish since it was used by Vasily
Smyslov several times! (Sometimes under a different move order).} 5. c3 Bd7 {
The most common move and Black's idea behind the move 4...d4.} (5... f5 {
This is an interesting alternative for Black when White can choose between the
simple and solid 6.d3 or the most ambitious 6.exf5! More on this can be found
in the theoretical analysis.}) 6. d4 g6 7. O-O Bg7 {We have reached the
starting position of the Smyslov Spanish. White has several ideas and possible
continuations, and the one I recommend is a good and practical one - to play
Be3 and to capture on e5! You can find this variation in the a6-d6 Smyslov
Spanish theory.}) 5. O-O Ng6 {Just like in the system with 3...Nge7, when I
see Ng6, I play d2-d4!. Although in this case, the concrete play can be very
different if Black includes 3...a6 4.Ba4.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 b5
9. Bb3 Bb7 10. Rd1 $1 {Remember this very important move! The point is that
after 10...c5, we have 11.Bxf7+! Further analysis can be found in the
theoretical chapter of this 4...Nge7 line.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Nge7 VARIATION"]
[Black "THEORY"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C60"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "41"]
[EventDate "2022.04.11"]
