{[%evp 0,41,25,12,13,25,29,17,5,-12,20,-1,42,13,28,28,76,30,43,35,44,44,87,39,
46,39,33,35,37,59,81,81,81,61,61,57,57,60,64,60,56,47,62,18]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 $5 {An interesting and playable alternative, but
White has ways to fight for the advantage!} 5. O-O $5 Ng6 (5... g6 6. c3 {
This will transpose to the 3...g6 system: 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.0-0
Nge7 (or 4...Bg7) 5.c3 a6 6.Ba4 that is analyzed in the next lesson.}) 6. d4 $1
{Just like in the system with 3...Nge7, when I see Ng6, I play d2-d4!.
Although in this case, the concrete play can be very different if Black
includes 3...a6 4.Ba4.} exd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 $1 {The most common move.} (7... Bc5
8. Be3 $1 {Continuing in the same manner as if 3...a6 4.Ba4 wasn't included.} (
8. Nf5 $5 {Is a good alternative.} O-O 9. Be3 Bxe3 10. Nxe3 d6 11. Nc3 $14)
8... Bxd4 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bb3 d6 12. Nc3 (12. Qe3 $5 Re8 13. Nc3
$14) 12... b5 13. Qd2 {With a typical small advantage for White thanks to the
e4 vs d6 pawns in the center.}) 8. Qxd4 b5 {There is no other sensible move
for Black.} 9. Bb3 Bb7 (9... c5 $4 10. Bxf7+ (10. Qd5 $18) 10... Kxf7 11. Qd5+
$18) (9... d6 $2 10. Bd5 Rb8 11. a4 c5 12. Qc3 b4 13. Qb3 $16) 10. Rd1 $3 {
REMEMBER THIS VERY IMPORTANT MOVE HERE! Threatening Bxf7+!! It is by far the
best move in the position!} (10. c4 {Also makes some sense to try to fight for
the space on the queenside, but 10.Rd1 is much better.}) 10... Qe7 $1 {The
only good move for Black, preventing Bxf7+ and threatening c5-c4.} (10... Bd6
$2 11. Qxg7 {Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn.} Rf8 (11...
Be5 12. Qxf7#) 12. Rxd6 $1 {It's not just that it's the best move in the
position, we should always play moves that make the opponent's game more
difficult.} (12. Qh6 $16 {Is an alternative if White doesn't want to sacrifice.
}) 12... cxd6 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. Bh6 $18) (10... d6 $6 {The threat of c7-c5 and
then c4 has been renewed, but White has a proper reply:} 11. c4 $1 c5 12. Qd3 (
12. Qe3 $14 {This is also playable for White.}) 12... Ne5 13. Qe2 Bc6 (13... b4
14. Bf4 $16 {Sooner or later, White will give a check on a4 and Black will be
in trouble.}) 14. Nc3 $16) (10... c5 $4 11. Bxf7+ $1 {The idea of Rd1!} Kxf7
12. Qxd7+ Be7 13. Qf5+ $18) {The position feels unnatural for Black, so it's
time for White to strike with:} 11. c4 $1 Qd6 $5 {The best move according to
the engines.} (11... c5 $6 12. Qe3 b4 {Black has to prevent Nc3 that would be
very strong, but he has too many weaknesses already.} 13. a3 $16 (13. Nd2 $5) (
13. Ba4 $5 Rd8 (13... O-O-O 14. Nd2 $16) 14. a3 $16) 13... O-O-O 14. axb4 Qxe4
(14... cxb4 15. c5 Qxe4 16. Qxe4 Bxe4 17. Be3 $1 Bc6 (17... Bb7 18. Nd2 $1 Ne5
19. Nc4 $1 Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Be7 21. Bxa6 $18) 18. Rxa6 $18 {Black is in a very
tough position.}) 15. Qxe4 Bxe4 16. Nc3 Bb7 17. b5 axb5 18. cxb5 $18) 12. Qxd6
$1 {This is the safest option, retaining a small advantage in the endgame.} (
12. Qe3 $5 {This is also possible, keeping the queens on the board, but Black
has some very unusual counterplay, so we better avoid it!} Qe5 $1 (12... Qc5 $2
13. Qh3 Bc6 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nc3 Bd6 16. Nd5 $1 $16 (16. Be3 $5 Qe5 17. Bd4
Qg5 18. Qf5 Qxf5 19. exf5 Nh4 20. Bxg7 Rg8 21. Re1+ Kd8 22. Bf6+ Kc8 23. Bxh4
Rxg2+ 24. Kf1 Rxh2 25. Bg3 Bxg3 26. fxg3 Rxb2 27. Re2 Rxe2 28. Kxe2 b4 29. Nd5
Bb5+ 30. Kd2 {1-0 Liang,A-Jacobson,B/chess.com INT 2022})) 13. cxb5 (13. Nc3
Bd6 $36) 13... Bd6 $1 (13... Bc5 14. Qf3 O-O 15. Bd5 $1 (15. Nc3 axb5 16. Be3
Bxe3 17. Qxe3 d6 18. Rd2 Rae8 19. Re1 $1 $14) 15... Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Qe7 17. Bg5
f6 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Rfb8 20. b6 Rxb6 21. b3 Re6 22. Qd2 $1 Rxe4 23. Nc3
Re5 24. Rxd7 Qe6 25. Rd1 $14) 14. Qg3 Qxg3 (14... Qxe4 15. Nc3 $1 Qf5 16. Qg5
Qxg5 17. Bxg5 f6 18. Be3 $16) 15. hxg3 axb5 16. Nc3 Bc6 17. Be3 h5 18. Rac1 {
White has a preferable position.} (18. f4 $5)) 12... Bxd6 13. Nc3 {Sadly
sacrificing on d6 isn't as good now as Black is better developed and has some
squares under control. White's idea is to simply develop the pieces with Be3,
and maybe even consolidate the center with f3 later on.} bxc4 $5 {This capture
is probably the best that Black can do.} (13... b4 14. Nd5 O-O-O (14... O-O 15.
Be3 Rfe8 16. f3 {Now f3 makes sense because f5 can be met with:} Bxd5 (16... f5
17. c5 $18) 17. Rxd5 $16) 15. Be3 Rhe8 16. Bc2 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 $14 (17. cxd5 $14)
) (13... Bc6 14. Be3 Rb8 (14... Be5 15. Rac1 (15. Nd5 $5 $14) 15... O-O 16. Rd2
Rfe8 17. f3 $14 {White's main goal is to consolidate the position, and only
then to move forward with a move like Nd5 for example.}) 15. Rab1 $14 (15. cxb5
axb5 16. f3 $14)) 14. Bxc4 {White's main idea is to stabilize the position,
and with that, White will have a comfortable edge. The position seems much
easier to play from the White side.} f6 $5 {Black may be hinting at the
possibility of 0-0-0 as the f7-pawn doesn't need to be protected anymore.} (
14... O-O 15. Be3 Rab8 16. Rac1 (16. b3 {White can play this move but there's
no rush, White can improve the pieces first instead.} Be5 17. Bd4 $14) 16...
Rfe8 17. f3 Ne5 18. Bb3 $14) 15. Be3 {It's important to understand that the
theory doesn't matter and this position is played on ideas. White needs to
play f3 sooner or later and aim to make progress in the center, also with a
move like Rac1 and then a possible Nd5.} Ne5 $5 (15... Ke7 16. Rac1 (16. Bd5 $5
$14 {I wouldn't like to exchange the bishops yet as it would give Black the
f7-square for the king, although this is also fine.}) (16. f3 $14) 16... Be5
17. f3 Bf4 18. Bxf4 (18. Kf2 $5 $14) 18... Nxf4 19. Kf2 $14 {White's pieces
are more active and White has a better pawn structure.}) 16. Bd5 $5 (16. Be2 $5
g5 $1 17. b4 $1 h5 (17... Bxb4 $2 18. Rab1 Bxc3 19. Rxb7 Ke7 (19... c6 $2 20.
Bh5+ $1 Kd8 21. Bb6+ Kc8 22. Rc7+ Kb8 23. Rb1 $18) 20. Rxc7 $16) 18. h3 Ke7 19.
Rab1 $14) 16... Bxd5 (16... Rb8 17. Ba7 $1 Ra8 18. Bd4 Rb8 19. Rab1 $14) 17.
Nxd5 Ng4 18. g3 Nxe3 19. Nxe3 Rb8 20. b3 (20. Rd2 $14) (20. Rac1 $14) 20... Bc5
21. Nc4 $14 {White has a good knight, a better pawn structure, and can still
improve the position, so it seems a bit more comfortable for White, although
of course, the position is playable for both sides.} *

