1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. O-O Ng6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 (
7... Bc5 {The typical positions in the pawn structure e4 vs d6 pawns should be
studied well, as they arise quite often in practical games and the model games
illustrate the ideas quite well.}) 8. Qxd4 {This line can even lead to an
endgame as you can see in the theoretical chapter, and it's good to see how
White should handle the position so you get a better feeling of how to play it
if it arises in your own games.} *

