1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. O-O Ng6 (5... g6 6. c3 {This
would transpose to the lines without a6 and Ba4 included.} (6. d4 {This direct
approach is also good.})) 6. d4 exd4 (6... b5 $2 7. Bb3 Nxd4 (7... exd4 8. Nxd4
Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bb7 10. Rd1 {Is analyzed in the theoretical chapter.}) 8. Ng5 $3 {
A very strong extra possibility for White.} Nxb3 9. Qd5 $18) 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Be3
Bxd4 9. Bxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bb3 {Stepping away from a tempo like b7-b5
and improving the bishop.} d6 12. Qe3 {Side-stepping c7-c5 just in case.} Re8
13. Nc3 c6 (13... Be6 14. Rad1 (14. f4 $5) 14... Bxb3 15. axb3 Qc8 16. Qd4 {
White is slightly preferable due to the e4 vs d6 pawn structure, with a long
game ahead.}) 14. Rad1 Qf6 15. Qd4 Qg5 16. Qxd6 Nf4 17. g3 {White is safe as
Black doesn't have anything after Nh3+.} Nh3+ 18. Kg2 Qh5 19. f3 {Controls the
light squares and prepares g3-g4.} Qg5 (19... Ng5 20. g4 $16) 20. Qd2 Qf6 21.
Qd4 Qh6 22. Qd2 Qh5 23. Ne2 {White managed to consolidate later on and little
by little, managed to win the game.} b5 24. g4 Qh4 25. Qe1 Qh6 26. Qd2 Ng5 27.
Ng1 a5 28. a3 Qf6 29. Qd4 Qh6 30. Qf2 Qf6 31. Qd4 Qg6 32. h3 h5 33. Rde1 hxg4
