{[%evp 0,31,42,42,31,41,18,13,28,-6,5,5,36,5,47,47,67,12,8,8,-1,-13,-2,7,33,38,
53,53,44,37,50,38,106,37]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... f5 4. d4 (4. d3
$1) 4... fxe4 5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. dxe5 c6 {This is a difference why we don't play
d4 after 3...f5, Black can play c6 here and not a6.} (6... a6 7. Ba4 {Would
reach the position with a6 and Ba4 included, where White has a winning
advantage.}) 7. Bc4 Qa5+ {Black will win the e5-pawn next.}) 4. Ba4 f5 $6 {
This line is more fashionable on rapid and blitz in comparison to classical
chess, although in my view, due to concrete reasons, it is better for Black to
try f5 on move 3 (without the inclusion of 3...a6 4.Ba4). Black can mainly use
this line occasionally as a surprise weapon.} 5. d4 $1 {The best move! Black
is playing mainly for tricks.} exd4 (5... fxe4 6. Nxe5 Nf6 (6... Nxe5 7. dxe5
$18) 7. O-O Be7 8. c3 $1 {Intending Qb3+ after Black castles.} Na5 (8... O-O 9.
Qb3+ d5 10. Nxc6 $18) 9. b4 Nc4 10. f3 $16 (10. Nxc4 $5 b5 11. Bg5 $16)) 6. e5
$1 {Next, White intends to play c3.} b5 (6... Bc5 $2 7. c3 d5 (7... dxc3 8.
Nxc3 Nge7 9. Bg5 $16 (9. O-O $16)) 8. cxd4 $16) 7. Bb3 Na5 $1 {White's
light-squared bishop is very powerful, so Black wants to eliminate it.} (7...
Bb7 $2 8. c3 $16 {Now we can also keep the light-squared bishop in case Black
plays Na5.} Na5 (8... d6 $2 9. Ng5 Qe7 10. O-O O-O-O 11. e6 $18) 9. Bc2 g6 (
9... dxc3 10. Nxc3 Bc5 11. Bxf5 Ne7 12. Bc2 (12. Be4 $16) 12... O-O 13. Ne4 $16
) (9... d6 10. O-O dxe5 11. Bxf5 {Black's king is still in the center so Black
needs to be very careful.}) 10. cxd4 $16 (10. O-O $16)) (7... d6 $2 8. exd6
Bxd6 9. O-O Na5 10. Re1+ Ne7 11. Qxd4 Nxb3 12. axb3 O-O 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Bxd6
cxd6 15. Nbd2 Kh8 16. Ng5 Qd7 17. Ne6 Rg8 18. Nc5 Qc6 19. Nxb7 Qxb7 20. Qxd6
Rad8 21. Qxe7 Qxe7 22. Rxe7 Rxd2 23. Rc7 Rgd8 24. h4 Rd1+ 25. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 26.
Kh2 h5 27. Kg3 Rd2 28. b4 Rd4 29. c3 Rd2 30. Rc6 Rxb2 31. Rxa6 Kh7 32. Rc6 Rc2
33. Kf3 Rb2 34. g3 Rc2 35. Ke3 g6 36. f3 Rg2 37. Kf4 Rc2 38. Kg5 Rg2 39. Rc7+
Kh8 40. Kh6 Kg8 41. Rg7+ Kf8 42. Rxg6 Rc2 43. Rg5 Rxc3 44. Rxf5+ Ke7 45. Kxh5 {
1-0 Novik,M-Becerra,J/chess.com INT 2024}) (7... Bc5 $2 8. c3 dxc3 9. Nxc3 $18
(9. O-O $18)) 8. Bd5 $1 {This is one good option for White, provoking c6 and
then capturing on g8.} (8. Nxd4 $1 {This is also very good for White.} Bb7 (
8... Nxb3 9. axb3 Bb7 10. O-O Qh4 11. Nc3 $14) 9. O-O Nxb3 10. Nxb3 {Black is
playing for tricks!} Qe7 (10... Qh4 11. Na5 $16) 11. a4 (11. Re1 O-O-O 12. Na5
Ba8 13. a4 $16) 11... b4 12. N1d2 O-O-O 13. Nc4 Qe6 14. Nca5 Ba8 15. Qe2 $16)
8... c6 (8... Bb7 $2 9. Bxb7 Nxb7 10. Nxd4 $18 {Black has a lot of weaknesses
and lacks king safety and development, so White's position is winning.}) 9.
Bxg8 Rxg8 10. c3 $1 (10. Nxd4 $5 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 (11... Bxd6 12. O-O $16 Qf6
13. Nf3 Kf7 14. Bg5 Qg6 15. Re1 Ra7 16. Bd2 Nc4 17. Ng5+ Kf8 18. Bf4 Re7 19.
Nxh7+ Ke8 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Rxe7+ Kxe7 22. Qxd6+ Kxd6 23. b3 Re8 24. Kf1 Be6
25. Ng5 Bd5 26. g3 Ne5 27. Nc3 Nf3 28. Nxd5 Nd2+ 29. Kg2 cxd5 30. Rd1 Re2 31.
Nh3 Ne4 32. Rxd5+ Kc6 33. Rxf5 Rxc2 34. a4 Rb2 35. axb5+ axb5 36. Ng5 Nc5 37.
Rf7 Nd3 38. h4 g6 39. Ne6 b4 40. Nf8 Rxb3 41. Nxg6 Ne1+ 42. Kh3 Rb1 43. h5 b3
44. h6 b2 45. h7 Nd3 46. Kg2 Rg1+ 47. Kxg1 b1=Q+ 48. Kh2 Qa2 49. Rf6+ {1-0
