{[%evp 0,31,16,28,25,20,12,13,17,-1,21,-42,1,-13,70,31,49,40,32,10,28,20,23,6,
7,3,24,-9,13,35,55,39,39,19]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 {This is
another playable and interesting system for Black. It is called Deffered
Steinitz or Smyslov Spanish since it was used by Vasily Smyslov several times!
(Sometimes under a different move order).} 5. c3 $5 {In most cases this move
will lead to the same position with the other main move 5.0-0} Bd7 {The most
common move and the main idea behind the early d6 move!} (5... f5 $5 {This is
an interesting and complicated alternative.} 6. exf5 (6. d3 $1 {This is a
simple and interesting continuation, for those who want to avoid all the
theory. The position is around equal but it's a lot easier to play with White!
Both sides have some interesting play, here are some sample lines:} fxe4 (6...
Nf6 7. Nbd2 $1 (7. exf5 $5 Bxf5 8. O-O Be7 9. d4 e4 10. d5 exf3 11. dxc6 b5 12.
Bb3 fxg2 13. Re1 $36) 7... fxe4 8. Nxe4 $5 $14) 7. dxe4 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 (8...
Nxe4 $4 9. Nxe5 $3 dxe5 10. Qh5+ Kd7 11. Qf5+ Ke8 12. Qxe4 $18) (8... Bd7 9.
Re1 Be7 10. Nbd2 Qc8 $1 11. Nf1 (11. Bb3 Na5 12. Bc2 $132) 11... O-O 12. Ng3
$132) 9. Re1 Bg4 (9... Bd7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Ng5 $14 Qe8 12. Bb3+ Kh8 13. Ne6
Bxe6 14. Bxe6 Nh5 15. Nf3 $14 Nd8 16. Bf5 $1 $14) 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nbd2 Nd7 (
11... O-O 12. Qb3+ Kh8 13. Qxb7 Na5 14. Qb4 c5 15. Qa3 $14) 12. Bb3 $5 Rf8 13.
Bc4 $1 Nb6 14. Be2 $16) 6... Bxf5 7. O-O Bd3 8. Re1 Be7 {This is a very old
line and is occasionally being used by Black as a surprise weapon.} 9. Bc2 {
This is a simple try for a small advantage.} Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Nf6 11. d4 $1 e4 12.
Ng5 d5 13. f3 $1 {White has to attack Black's strong center immediately.
Trying to attack with moves like Ne6 is bad because it's just one piece in the
attack with no support.} h6 $1 (13... exf3 $2 14. Ne6 $1 Qd7 15. Bf4 Kf7 16.
Ng5+ Kg8 17. Nxf3 $16) 14. Nh3 O-O (14... exf3 $2 15. Qg6+ Kf8 (15... Kd7 16.
Qf5+ Ke8 17. Qxf3 $16) 16. Nf4 $18) 15. Nd2 $1 exf3 16. Nxf3 $14 {White's
position is slightly easier to play due to the weaknesses on the central
squares. The position resembles a French Exchange with an extra open f-file.}
Qd7 $5 (16... Rf7 17. Nf2 (17. Bf4 $5 Ne4 18. c4 $1 $14) 17... Bd6 18. Bd2 $14)
(16... Ne4 $6 17. Nf4 Rf7 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Rxe4 $18) 17. Bf4 Bd6 (17... Ne4
18. c4 Nb4 (18... Bb4 $4 19. cxd5 $18) 19. Qb3 $16 {Everything is hanging for
Black.}) 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Re2 $14 {The issue for Black is the misplaced
knight on c6, so White's position is more comfortable.} Rae8 20. Rae1 Rxe2 (
20... Ne4 $6 21. Nf2 $14) 21. Rxe2 Ne4 22. Nd2 Nxd2 23. Qxd2 $14) 6. d4 g6 (
6... Nf6 7. Nbd2 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Re1 O-O 12.
Nf1 $14) 7. O-O Bg7 {We have reached the starting position of the Smyslov
Spanish. White has several ideas and possible continuations, and of course, we
will choose a good and practical one - to play Be3 and then to capture on e5!
Remember: no matter what move order Black chooses, our plan should be to
capture on e5, either right away or after some developing moves first. This
will take us to some symmetrical position with only the d-file being open,
when White will have a risk-free advantage thanks to the more active pieces.}
8. Be3 $1 Nf6 $1 (8... Nge7 $2 {The knight is misplaced on the e7-square in
this particular position since Black can't really go for the f5 pawn break,
and yet, many strong players, even good grandmasters, commit this mistake with
Black!} 9. dxe5 $1 dxe5 (9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 {And now, several options
lead to an advantage and a risk-free game.} 11. f3 (11. Bb3 O-O 12. Nd2 $16) (
11. Nd2 $16) 11... Bxa4 12. Qxa4+ Qd7 13. Qb3 $1 O-O 14. Rd1 Qc6 15. Na3 $16)
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Re1 b6 12. Nf1 $14 (12. h3 $5)) (8... b5 {This won't change
much and the plans remain the same. Now additionally, the c5-square as well as
the whole queenside has been weakened for Black.} 9. Bc2 (9. Bb3 $5 $14 Nge7 $6
10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Bc5 $16) 9... Nf6 10. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 11. Nxe5
dxe5 12. Nd2 (12. Bc5 $2 Bf8 $1 {This is very simple for Black, so we should
avoid it.}) 12... O-O 13. h3 Qe7 14. Nb3 Rfd8 15. Qe2 $14) 9. dxe5 $1 {A
simple and good approach. Now, the theoretical part is practically over!} dxe5
(9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. f3 $1 $14 {Note that we don't want to exchange
queens when Black can bring his king into the center. We can consider
exchanging them once Black has castled and the king is further away, so Black
has to spend tempos later on to activate it.} (11. Bxd7+ $6 Qxd7 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7
$1 13. f3 Ke6 $132) 11... O-O (11... Bxa4 12. Qxa4+ Qd7 13. Qb3 $1 Qc6 14. Na3
O-O 15. Qc4 $1 $16 {Black will suffer in this endgame with no winning
prospects at all for him.}) (11... b5 12. Bc2 O-O (12... Qe7 13. b4 $14) 13.
Nd2 Qe7 14. Nb3 Rfd8 15. Qe2 $14) 12. Nd2 (12. Bxd7 $5 Qxd7 13. Qxd7 $1 {
Now that the Black king is away from the center, White can consider playing
this risk-free endgame!} Nxd7 14. Rd1 Rfd8 15. Nd2 Bf8 16. Nc4 $1 f6 17. Na5
$14 (17. Kf1 $14 Bc5 $4 18. Rxd7 $18)) 12... Re8 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Nc4 (14. Nb3
$5 $14) 14... Qc6 15. Na5 $1 Qb5 16. b4 $14) 10. Nbd2 {And again, there is no
need for any concrete theory. Both players have many playable moves but in all
scenarios, White is the one with the more active pieces. Just note that we
don't want to give up the bishop on e3 for a knight, for example after a
well-timed Ng4, so before that, we need to play h3 at some moment. Here are
some sample lines:} Qe7 11. h3 (11. b4 $5 b6 12. h3 (12. Qc2 $5 Ng4 13. Bg5 $14
) 12... O-O 13. Qc2 Nh5 14. Bb3 Kh8 15. a4 f5 16. Nc4 $1 Nf4 (16... f4 17. Bc1
$14) 17. Rae1 $14) 11... O-O 12. Re1 (12. b4 $5 $14) 12... Nh5 13. Qc2 Kh8 14.
Rad1 b6 (14... f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Nb3 $1 $16) 15. Nf1 Rad8 16. Qc1 $14 (16.
Rd5 $5 Nf4 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Qd2 $16) *

