1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. c3 Bd7 6. d4 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Be3 {
We reach a typical position for this line when I recommend for White to soon
capture the pawn on e5. The arising positions are kind of symmetrical, so in a
practical game, you will need to show a good technique to win the game. White
will have more active pieces in most cases, so it's very good to see how the
players from the White side handled the position and converted it into a full
point!} *

