1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 (3... a6 4. Ba4 d6 {This is the move order that
we are discussing, the game went differently but it eventually transposes to
the topical discussion.} 5. c3 Bd7 6. d4 g6 7. O-O Bg7 {The initial position
of the Deffered Steinitz variation, which I would also like to call the
Smyslov variation. This position can be reached via several move orders.} 8.
Be3 Nf6 9. dxe5) 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 d6 (6... Nge7 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 b5
9. Bc2 d6 10. h3 O-O 11. Nc3 {This line was studied previously.}) 7. d4 Bd7 8.
Be3 {This is the move that I recommend for White.} Nf6 (8... Nge7 {This isn't
the way to go for Black as White can capture on e5 sooner or later and will
have a favorable position.} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... dxe5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Re1 h6 12.
b4 $14) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Nd2 $14) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Nd2 {11.f3
is also good.} O-O 12. f3 Qe7 (12... b5 {This weakens the c5-square.} 13. Bc2
$1 (13. Bb3 $2 Qe7 {And Black will manage to play c5 on the next move.}) 13...
Qe7 14. Nb3 $14 (14. b4 {This is also possible, intending Bc5.})) 13. Bxd7 Nxd7
(13... Qxd7 14. Qb3 b6 15. Rfd1 Qc6 16. Qc4 Qb7 17. Nb3 a5 18. a4 $14) 14. Qb3
b6 15. Qc4 {Quite often, the c4-square is a very nice square for the queen in
these types of positions.} Nf6 (15... c5 16. a4 {Preventing b5.} Rfb8 17. Rfd1
(17. Qe2 $5 $14 {Is also fine but I don't mind b5 so much.}) 17... b5 18. axb5
axb5 19. Qd5 $14) 16. Qc6 Qd7 17. Qxd7 Nxd7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. Nc4 Nf8 20. Rd5
Ne6 21. Kf1 f6 22. Ke2 Kf7 23. g3 Bf8 24. b4 b5 25. Na5 c6 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. a4
Rc8 28. Nb3 bxa4 29. Rxa4 c5 30. bxc5 Rc6 31. f4 h5 32. h3 Rc7 33. Rc4 Rb7 34.
Nc1 exf4 35. gxf4 Bxc5 36. f5 1-0

