1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 d6 6. d4 Bd7 7. O-O Bg7 8. Be3
Nf6 (8... b5 9. Bc2 Nf6 10. Nbd2 $5 {Keeping flexibility in the position since
Ng4 isn't a threat, so this seems a bit more accurate than capturing on e5
right away.} (10. dxe5 $5 $14) 10... O-O (10... Ng4 11. Bg5 $14) 11. dxe5 Nxe5
12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. f3 $14 {With Nb3 next, when White again has the same
risk-free type of game.}) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. f3 (11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12.
Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. f3 Ke6 {Black's king is more active in comparison to g8, so we
wait for Black to castle first before exchanging on d7.}) 11... O-O (11... Bxa4
12. Qxa4+ Qd7 13. Qb3 {I wouldn't like to exchange the queens yet.} b6 14. Nd2
O-O 15. Rfd1 $14) 12. Bxd7 {Now since Black has castled and his king is
further away from the center, we can capture on d7.} Qxd7 13. Qxd7 Nxd7 14. Rd1
Rfd8 15. Nd2 Bf8 16. Nc4 b5 17. Na5 Bc5 18. Kf2 Bxe3+ 19. Kxe3 Nb6 20. b3 {
White has the better king, better knight, and can execute a pawn break on the
queenside, so White has the advantage.} f6 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rc1 Nc8 23. c4
Rd7 24. cxb5 axb5 25. Rc5 {White has chances now to create a distant passed
pawn.} Na7 26. Nc6 Nxc6 27. Rxc6 Kf7 28. Ke2 f5 29. exf5 gxf5 30. Rc5 Ke6 31.
Rxb5 c6 32. Rb8 Kd5 33. Kd3 Kc5+ 34. Kc3 f4 35. Re8 Kd5 36. a4 Rg7 37. Rd8+ Kc5
38. Rd2 Rb7 39. Re2 Kd5 40. b4 Ra7 41. Rd2+ Ke6 42. Kb3 e4 43. fxe4 Ke5 44. Re2
Rg7 45. Kc4 h5 46. a5 h4 47. h3 1-0

