1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 g6 {As you can see in the next lesson, I
offer the move d4 as a second choice in this position, just in case you don't
want to transpose.} 5. c3 d6 6. d4 Bd7 7. O-O Bg7 8. dxe5 $5 {This is in the
same spirit as 8.Be3 followed by dxe5, and it may even transpose.} dxe5 9. Be3
Nf6 10. Nbd2 O-O (10... Ng4 11. Bg5 {This is the usual reply for White against
Ng4, but in this case, 11.Bc5 looks stronger.} (11. Bc5 $1 $16)) 11. Re1 Re8
12. h3 {White should play h3 sooner or later.} Qc8 13. Qe2 Nd8 14. Bxd7 Nxd7
15. Red1 Ne6 16. a4 {Keep in mind that the c4-square is important as either
the queen or the knight will go there.} Nb8 17. Qc4 $16 Nc6 18. b4 Rd8 19. Nb3
Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Qe8 21. Ng5 Rd8 22. Rxd8 Ncxd8 23. Nxe6 Nxe6 24. Na5 b5 25. axb5
axb5 26. Qd5 Nf4 27. Qd2 h5 28. h4 Ne6 29. g3 Qa8 30. Qd5 Qxd5 31. exd5 Nd8 32.
c4 bxc4 33. Nxc4 f6 34. b5 Bf8 35. Ba7 Kf7 36. Bb8 Ke7 37. Bxc7 Nb7 38. Kf1 Kd7
39. b6 e4 40. Ke2 Bc5 41. Nd2 f5 42. Nc4 1-0

