{In this lesson, three systems will be discussed: 1) The delayed g6 line with
4...g6; 2) The Old Archangelsk; 3) a6-Bc5-Nge7 system for Black;} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 {4...Bc5 after including 3...a6 4.Ba4 is a
playable and very popular system. It's good to note that Bc5 on the fourth
move is better than 3...Bc5, however, there are a few ways for White to fight
for the advantage, and here I offer a very easy one with c3 and d4 right away!}
(4... b5 5. Bb3 Nf6 6. d3 Bb7 7. O-O {Also reaches the Old Archangelsk
position.}) (4... Nf6 {This move will be examined in the upcoming lessons, but
for now in this lesson, it will be connected with the pawn push b7-b5 and Bb7.}
5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 7. O-O {This is the Old Archangelsk variation that can be
reached by many move orders, that shouldn't confuse us but in fact should make
it easier for us, as eventually, we reach the same position.} Be7 {Amongst
other moves, this is the most played one, and now White has:} 8. c4 $1 {
And White reaches a very comfortable position after this. You can find the
analysis in the theory chapter of the Old Archangelsk variation.}) (4... g6 5.
d4 $1 {This move order with 4...g6 is not the same as g6 on move 3. Now, we
are offered a very interesting alternative 5.d4! This move is not as good if
it's played without the inclusion of a6 and Ba6, here it's better. In any case,
if you want you can continue with 5.c3 or even 5.0-0 followed by 6.c3, and
then we would transpose to the lines arising from 3...g6, with the typical
play after c3-d4 happens on the board.} exd4 (5... b5 {The right continuation
for Black, although most players capture on d4 right away. This continuation
leads to some concrete theory that should be memorized and can't be avoided,
but White gets a pleasant position afterward. You can find more analysis in
the theoretical chapter.}) 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {And this is the
difference why we can go d4 with the inclusion of 3...a6 and 4.Ba4. If they
weren't included, the bishop would be on b5 and it would be under attack with
tempo in this case.} 8. Nc3 {When White has a very comfortable position, you
can check the theory chapter of the delayed ...g6 move for further analysis of
this position and the move 5...b5.}) 5. c3 Nge7 6. d4 {Castling short leads to
an entirely different position, so it's important to play d4 now. You can find
the analysis in the theoretical file for this a6+Bc5+Nge7 system.} *

