{[%evp 0,33,28,19,22,23,16,16,28,0,56,40,76,63,70,57,56,65,54,54,41,67,32,24,
96,25,40,32,46,-40,49,47,47,41,54,41]} 1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} e5 {[%emt 0:00:
39]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:12]} 3. Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} a6 {
[%emt 0:00:09]} (3... g6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 $6 Bg7 $1 {This is the difference
why we don't play 3...Bg7 4.d4, because in this position, when we capture Nxc6,
Black can recapture bxc6 and it will hit our bishop with tempo - the bishop is
not on a4 in comparison to when a6 and Ba4 are included, so Black is doing
well in this position.}) 4. Ba4 {[%emt 0:00:18] This move order with 4...g6 is
not the same as g6 on move 3. Now, we are offered a very interesting
alternative 5.d4! This move is not as good if it's played without the
inclusion of a6 and Ba6, here it's better. In any case, if you want you can
continue with 5.c3 or even 5.0-0 followed by 6.c3, and then we would transpose
to the lines arising from 3...g6, with the typical play after c3-d4 happens on
the board.} g6 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 5. d4 $1 {[%emt 0:18:58]} (5. c3 d6 (5... Bg7
6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bc2 d6 9. h3 Nge7 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 {Transposes to
lines analyzed previously.}) 6. d4 Bd7 7. O-O Bg7 8. Be3 {Also transposes.})
5... b5 $1 {[%emt 0:00:27]} (5... exd4 $6 {This move isn't as good as 5...b5
but everyone plays it!} 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 8. Nc3 {Once again, no
concrete theory is required here, White is at least slightly better with moves
like Be3 (or Bg5), Qd2, and Bh6!, while Bb3 at some point will be played too.
The knight is quite misplaced on e7 since Black doesn't and shouldn't intend
to play f7-f5.} Ne7 (8... Nf6 {This is a move that Black would like to play,
to develop the knight on f6 and not on e7 but it runs into} 9. e5 $16) 9. O-O
Rb8 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Be3 d6 12. Bd4 $14 (12. Qd2 $14)) 6. Bb3 {[%emt 0:01:35]} (
6. d5 $2 Na5 7. Bb3 d6 8. O-O Bg7 9. c4 Bd7 $15) 6... exd4 {[%emt 0:00:07] Now
is the time for Black to capture on d4.} 7. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:04:25] White might
be threatening Nxc6.} (7. a4 $5 b4 8. Nxd4 Na5 {Transposes below.}) 7... Na5 $1
{[%emt 0:00:07] This is a playable system for Black, but White should have
some advantage. The play now becomes very concrete for the next few moves.} (
7... Nge7 $4 8. Qf3 $18) (7... Bb7 8. Nxc6 $1 Bxc6 (8... dxc6 9. Qxd8+ (9. Qf3
$5 $16) 9... Rxd8 10. f3 Bg7 11. a4 $16) 9. Nc3 $16) 8. a4 $1 {[%emt 0:07:12]
This is a move that White should remember!} (8. Qf3 $5) 8... b4 {[%emt 0:00:06]
} (8... c5 9. Bd5 {Avoids c5-c4.}) (8... Nxb3 9. Nxb3 $14) 9. Bd5 $1 {[%emt 0:
01:06] Provoking c6.} c6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 10. Ba2 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bg7 {
[%emt 0:00:06]} 11. c3 {[%emt 0:03:40]} (11. Nf3 $5 {Is also good. is also
very good} d6 12. O-O Ne7 13. c3 $14) 11... c5 {[%emt 0:32:31]} (11... Rb8 $2
12. O-O $16) 12. cxb4 $1 cxb4 13. O-O Ne7 {Intending to castle, play Bb7, and
maybe even d7-d5.} 14. Nd2 $3 {A computer move, but the knight on d4 is immune
to capture as White would get an advantage.} (14. Be3 O-O 15. Nd2 d5 $15) (14.
Nf3 O-O 15. Nbd2 d5 16. exd5 Bb7 $1 $15 (16... Nxd5 17. Ne4 b3 $1 18. Bxb3 Nxb3
19. Qxb3 Bf5 20. Bg5 Qd7 21. Nc5 Qc6 $36)) 14... O-O (14... Bxd4 15. Nc4 Bg7 (
15... Nac6 16. Nd6+ Kf8 17. Qxd4 Nxd4 18. Bh6+ Kg8 19. Bxf7# {A beautiful line!
}) 16. Nd6+ Kf8 17. Nxf7 $18 {We are not just going for the two pieces for a
rook, White also has an attack that can even end in checkmate.}) 15. N2f3 {
Black would like to play d7-d5 but it's not that good as White can simply pass
it with e5.} Bb7 16. Re1 Nec6 17. Be3 $14 {White has an advantage thanks to
the more active pieces.} *

