121,136,131,130,125]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 g6 5. d4 exd4 6.
Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bb3 (10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 {
It's better to retreat the bishop to e3 as now Black can follow up with:} Rb8
12. Bb3 (12. Rb1 g5 13. Bg3 d6 14. Bb3 Ng6 $132) 12... g5 13. Bg3 Ng6 $1 14.
Qd2 d6 15. Rad1 a5 16. Rfe1 Re8 $132) 10... d6 11. Be3 {White can exchange the
dark-squared bishops with Bd4 next.} Kh8 12. Qd2 (12. Bd4 $5) 12... Ng8 {
As we can observe, the knight was misplaced on e7 and now Black spends a lot
of tempi to improve it.} 13. Rad1 f5 14. Bd4 (14. exf5 $5 {Capturing the pawn
is also interesting since Black's knight can't recapture. If the knight was on
e7, something like Bd4 or Bh6 would have been the reply, although it always
depends on the concrete position.} Bxf5 15. Bd4 $16 {Opening up the f-file
didn't accomplish much for Black.}) 14... Bxd4 15. Qxd4+ Qf6 16. Rfe1 Qxd4 17.
Rxd4 Nf6 18. e5 Re8 19. f4 Bb7 20. Rb4 Ra7 21. Ba4 Re6 22. Re2 Nh5 23. exd6
Rxe2 24. Nxe2 cxd6 25. Rb6 c5 26. Rxd6 Be4 27. c4 Re7 28. Bd1 Bc2 29. Kf2 Bxd1
30. Rxd1 Re4 31. Rd8+ Kg7 32. Rd7+ Kh6 33. g3 Nf6 34. Ra7 Ng4+ 35. Ke1 Nxh2 36.
Rxa6 Rxc4 37. Kd1 Ng4 38. Ra3 Nf2+ 39. Ke1 Ne4 40. Kd1 Rb4 41. Kc2 Rb7 42. Re3
Kh5 43. a4 Ra7 44. Ra3 Ra5 45. Kd3 Nd6 46. Kc3 Kg4 47. b4 Ne4+ 48. Kc4 Nd2+ 49.
Kc3 Nb1+ 50. Kb3 Nd2+ 51. Kc3 Ne4+ 52. Kc4 Nd6+ 53. Kb3 cxb4 54. Kxb4 Rd5 55.
a5 Rd2 56. Nc3 Rb2+ 57. Kc5 Nb7+ 58. Kd4 Nxa5 59. Rxa5 Kxg3 60. Nd5 Rb7 61.
Ra3+ Kg4 62. Ke5 1-0

