1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 (4... Nf6 {This move will be examined
in the upcoming lessons below, but for now in this chapter, it will be
connected with the pawn push b7-b5 and Bb7 - the Old Archangelsk.} 5. d3 b5 6.
Bb3 Bb7 7. O-O Be7 {This is another way to get the Old Archangelsk with d3.})
5. Bb3 Nf6 (5... Bb7 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3 {Is another move order to reach this
position.}) 6. d3 Bb7 7. O-O {In this variation, White has a way to get at
least a slightly better position, but the annoying thing for the opponent
might be that it's essentially a risk-free game for White.} Be7 $5 {This is
considered to be better than Bc5.} (7... Bc5 $6 8. Be3 $1 {I like this move a
lot here due to the bad bishop on b7!} (8. a3 $5 O-O 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11.
Bxd5 Rb8 12. b4 Bb6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. fxe3 Ne7 15. Bb3 $14) 8... Bxe3 9. fxe3
O-O 10. Nc3 (10. Qe1 $5 {Is also good, preventing Na5 and bringing the queen
closer to the kingside, preparing Nh4 at the same time.} d6 11. a3 Bc8 12. Nc3
Be6 13. d4 Bxb3 14. cxb3 $14) 10... d6 11. a3 $14 {In all these positions, we
can clearly see a misplaced bishop on b7 hitting into White's wall of pawns e4
supported by d3.}) (7... Bd6 $6 {This may be playable but it's not very
impressive. White has a few ways to get an advantage.} 8. a4 (8. Bg5 $5 h6 9.
Bh4 O-O 10. a4 b4 11. Nbd2 $14) (8. a3 $5 O-O 9. Nc3 h6 10. Ba2 $5 $14) 8...
O-O (8... b4 9. Nbd2 Bc5 10. Nc4 d6 11. c3 $16) 9. axb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Qxa8 11.
Bg5 Be7 12. Nc3 $14) 8. c4 $3 {This relatively rare move is very powerful
here! This isn't a good move often, but in this position, the main reason why
it works is because Black's bishop is on b7, and for example, there is no Bg4
to take over the d4-square that we just weakened.} O-O (8... bxc4 9. Bxc4 O-O
10. Nc3 {Transposes.}) (8... d6 9. Nc3 (9. Na3 $5 Na7 10. Nc2 {Is also
playable.}) 9... bxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O 11. a3 {Transposes.}) (8... b4 $6 9. Ba4 $1
{The bishop finds itself a nice square to be active from, threatening Bxc6 and
Nxe5 now.} d6 10. a3 a5 11. Bd2 $14) 9. Nc3 bxc4 (9... b4 10. Nd5 $16) 10. Bxc4
d6 {If now Black can manage to get Na5 in and capture our bishop, Black will
be doing fine, however, it's White to move.} 11. a3 $14 {White is at least
slightly better and can continue with expanding on the queenside with b4 or to
prepare a timely d2-d4. Here are some sample lines:} Nd4 (11... Na5 12. Ba2 c5
13. b4 $1 (13. Rb1 $5 $14) 13... cxb4 14. axb4 Nc6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Qd7
17. Bd2 Na7 18. Qb3 $14 (18. Bc4 $5 Nb5 19. Qb3 $14)) (11... Bc8 $6 12. h3 Be6
13. Be3 $1 $16 (13. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Be3 Qe8 15. Rc1 (15. b4 $16) 15... Nh5 16.
b4 $16 Nf4 17. Bxf4 Rxf4 18. Ne2 $18) 13... Bxc4 14. dxc4 a5 15. Qc2 $16) 12.
Nxd4 (12. b4 $5 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 c6 14. Bb3 Bc8 15. Bd2 {When White's position
is a bit more comfortable.}) 12... exd4 13. Nd5 $1 {This is a very good idea,
capturing on d4 and then jumping in with Nd5.} Nxd5 14. exd5 {And once again,
no concrete theory is needed anymore. White has easy moves like Bd2, b4, Re1
and so on, while Black's position is passive.} Re8 (14... a5 15. Bd2 Bg5 16.
Re1 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Re8 18. Qf4 $16) (14... Bg5 15. b4 a5 16. b5 Bxc1 17. Rxc1
Qg5 18. Re1 $16 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. a4 Rac8 21. Rc6 {When White has a big
advantage thanks to the weak c7-pawn as a target and strong pawn on b5.}) 15.
Qg4 (15. Bd2 $5 $16) 15... Bf6 16. Bd2 Rb8 17. b4 {Later on, White's idea can
be to play a4-a5 and then b5, creating a passed a-pawn, or another version of
it is to play a4, and then b5 and once Black captures on b5, to recapture with
the bishop.} Bc8 18. Qd1 Qd7 19. Qf3 Qa4 20. Rfb1 Re5 21. Bf4 Re7 22. h3 Qd7
23. Bd2 Re5 24. a4 Rf5 25. Qd1 h5 26. b5 axb5 27. Bxb5 Qd8 28. a5 Bb7 29. Bc4
Bxd5 30. Bxd5 Rxd5 31. a6 Ra8 32. a7 c6 33. Rb7 Rb5 34. Rb1 Qc8 35. R1xb5 cxb5
36. Qf3 Qe8 37. Qd5 h4 38. Rxf7 Qxf7 39. Qxa8+ {1-0 Nakamura,H-Artemiev,V/
chess24.com INT 2021} *

