threat.}) 12... Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 (13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nd4 15. Qd1 {The knight on
d4 is strong but the rest of Black's pieces are passive, so White is doing
well, when the next moves can be Ne2 or Be3.}) 14. Be3 Qd7 15. Rc1 Nd8 {
Stepping away from any b4-b5 threats.} 16. d4 {Pushing the d-pawn makes sense
as White is striking the center but also, the bishop can retreat to e2 to
break the pin.} (16. Kh1 $5 {A very nice idea! Intending g4.}) 16... exd4 17.
Bxd4 Ne6 18. Be3 Rfd8 19. Qe2 c6 20. Rfd1 (20. Bxa6 $2 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Nh5 $19)
20... Qb7 21. g4 {The right moment to break the pin.} d5 22. Ba2 Bg6 23. Ne5 d4
