1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 $5 {4...Bc5 after including 3...a6 4.
Ba4 is a playable and a very popular system. It's good to note that Bc5 on the
fourth move is better than 3...Bc5, however, there are a few ways for White to
fight for the advantage, and here I offer a very easy one with c3 and d4 right
away!} 5. c3 $1 Nge7 {Black's idea is likely to get the knight to g6 later on.}
(5... Nf6 {Black can't afford the time to play this because after} 6. d4 exd4
7. e5 $16 {This is a very powerful continuation for White.}) 6. d4 $1 {
Castling short leads to an entirely different position, that's why it's
important to play d4 now.} exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ $1 (7... Ba7 $2 {Is simply bad
for Black.} 8. d5 $16 Na5 9. O-O O-O 10. Bc2 d6 11. b3 $3 $16 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5
13. Qd3) 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 $1 {A very simple continuation, playing for a
small advantage without the need to study much theory. Now White threatens
d4-d5 so Black is forced to play d7-d5 to prevent it.} d5 (9... b5 $2 10. Bc2
$16 (10. Bb3 $5 $16)) (9... O-O $2 10. d5 Nb4 11. O-O d6 12. Bb3 (12. Qe2 $5
$16) 12... a5 13. a3 Na6 14. Re1 {With a very pleasant advantage for White.})
10. e5 $1 {Long term, White space advantage in the center and the difficulty
for Black to create a passed pawn on the queenside give White an advantage.}
O-O (10... Bg4 $5 {Threatening b5 and then Nxd4.} 11. h3 $1 ({A good
alternative is} 11. Qc1 $5 {intending Qc3 and to strengthen the defense of the
center, while there is a chance this leads to a transposition to the lines
below.}) 11... Bh5 (11... Bxf3 $2 {White has a strategically winning position
after this.} 12. Nxf3 O-O 13. O-O {There is no need to exchange the bishop on
c6 but instead, White will retreat it to c2 to put pressure on Black's
kingside.} Qc8 (13... f6 14. Re1 fxe5 15. dxe5 $16) 14. Rc1 Nd8 15. Bc2 $16)
12. Qc1 $1 (12. O-O $2 b5 13. Bb3 Nxd4 $15) 12... O-O 13. O-O {Black should
sooner or later push f6, otherwise White will simply strengthen the position
with moves like Qc3, Rfe1, and Rac1.} Qd7 $2 (13... f6 14. Bxc6 $1 Nxc6 15. Qc3
fxe5 16. Nxe5 $1 (16. dxe5 $6 Qd7 $132 {Now our knight are a bit passive.})
16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 c6 18. Nb3 $5 $16 (18. Qd4 Qe7 19. f4 $1 Bg6 20. g4 $16 {
Is also a possible way to go.})) 14. Qc3 $16 {Since b7-b5 is quite bad for now,
there is no reason to capture on c6 with the bishop.} (14. Bxc6 Nxc6 15. Qc3
$14) 14... b5 15. Bd1 $16 (15. Bc2 $5) 15... Nd8 16. Rc1 Ne6 17. Ng5 Bxd1 18.
Nxe6 fxe6 19. Rfxd1 Rae8 20. Nb3 Ng6 21. Rd2 Nf4 22. Kh2 Qf7 23. g3 Ng6 24. Qd3
c6 25. Qe2 Ne7 26. Rdc2 h5 27. h4 Qg6 28. Nc5 Nf5 29. Rd2 Nxh4 30. gxh4 Rf4 31.
Rc3 $18) 11. O-O {White has a pleasant advantage due to his extra space in the
center. Black is not in a position to put too much pressure on d4, partly
because at some moment we will exchange on c6 - reducing the number of Black's
knights! Our basic ideas involve the moves: Bxc6 - Nxc6 and then Qb3!,
possibly followed by Qc3 or Qe3, strengthening the center, and another typical
idea we may also need is Qc1! - unpinning the Nf3 and following up with
Qc3-Qe3, and maybe Bxc6 later on.} Bf5 $5 {On one hand, this move doesn't put
pressure on our center but on the other hand, there may be some ideas with Nb4,
so it's an interesting move.} (11... f6 12. exf6 $1 Rxf6 13. Re1 Bg4 (13... Bf5
14. Bxc6 $1 Nxc6 15. Qb3 a5 16. a3 h6 17. Rac1 $14 (17. Qc3 $14)) 14. Bxc6 $1
Nxc6 15. Qb3 Rb8 16. Rac1 $16 {Such positions after exf6, Rxf6 and Bxc6
followed by Qb3 appears to be bad for Black as he has too many weaknesses.}
Bxf3 17. Nxf3 h6 {Now it's time to strengthen our position!} 18. Re3 $1 (18.
Rc5 $5 Ne7 19. Rc2 c6 20. Rce2 $14) 18... Qd6 (18... Rxf3 19. gxf3 Nxd4 20. Qd3
$16) 19. Rce1 $14 (19. Qd3 $5)) (11... Bg4 {Transposes to 10...Bg4.}) 12. a3 $1
f6 (12... a5 13. Rc1 $16) 13. exf6 Rxf6 14. Bxc6 $1 Nxc6 15. Qb3 $14 Rg6 16.
Kh1 Rb8 17. Rac1 Qd6 18. Rc5 $1 (18. Rfe1 $5 $14) 18... Be6 19. Rxc6 $1 Qxc6
20. Ne5 Qe8 21. Nxg6 Qxg6 22. Nf3 $16 *

