{[%evp 0,79,18,28,28,21,29,29,25,3,23,21,23,14,19,25,25,25,25,24,14,10,10,6,21,
-18,23,-6,5,12,15,23,23,21,30,9,11,6,7,4,19,0,14,21,20,2,14,-13,5,-11,10,-9,31,
32,47,-4,127,152,128,132,120,120,120,108,108,97,94,97,93,93,87,92,162,174,173,
172,176,178,188,189,188,186]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 5. c3
Nge7 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 d5 10. e5 O-O 11. O-O Bf5 {
With this move, Black doesn't put pressure on our center so we can simply
strengthen our position.} 12. Re1 f6 13. exf6 Rxf6 14. Bxc6 {This is a key
move very often! Exchanging the bishop and having two knights in the position
against one, and then with the intention to play Qb3 next.} (14. Qb3 $4 b5 $19)
14... Nxc6 15. Qb3 {In general just to note, it's important to protect the
f3-knight just in case of any potential sacrifices like Bg4-Bxf3 and Rxf3.} b6
16. Qc3 Qd7 17. Rac1 Raf8 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 c6 20. Rce1 Bg6 21. f3 {
Black's counterplay has been prevented and White enjoys a pleasant advantage.}
Re8 22. Qb4 Qd8 23. Nf1 Rxe5 24. Rxe5 Bf7 25. Qe1 Kf8 26. Ne3 (26. b4 {
Intending a4-a5 is also an idea at some point.}) 26... Re6 27. Nf5 Qd7 28. Qb4+
c5 29. dxc5 bxc5 30. Qxc5+ Kg8 31. Rxe6 Qxe6 32. Ne7+ Kh8 33. Qc8+ Qxc8 34.
Nxc8 d4 35. a3 Bc4 36. Kf2 Kg8 37. Ne7+ Kf8 38. Nc6 d3 39. Ke3 Bb5 40. Ne5 1-0

