1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 {In this lecture we are going to see
Berlin defense. This is one of the most solid openings ever and our approach
is to not go into a theoretical battle, rather play a position which can be
played by plans and ideas.} 5. O-O {This move is much rare compared to other
mainlines.} Nd4 6. Be3 (6. Nxd4 {Used to be the mainline and Black usually
gets a comfortable position.}) 6... Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Bxe3 8. Qxe3 {These are the
typical positions we are aiming for. White will play an order of Bc4-Bb3 to
avoid getting tempoed by c6-d5, Nbd2, f4, take on e5 and play a slow
middlegame/endgame, that is practically better for us.} *

