1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {The Berlin Spanish, a tough nut to crack!} 4.
d3 $1 {After this move. a big fight in the middlegame is to take place!} Bc5 $1
{By far the most common move, however there are some playable alternatives.} (
4... Ne7 $6 {not too impressive, Black's idea is to keep the Knight on g6.} 5.
Bc4 $1 (5. Nxe5 $4 {looses material.} c6 6. Bc4 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 Qxe5 {followed by
Qe5.}) 5... c6 (5... Ng6 $2 6. h4 $16 {White is better with threats like h5,
Ng5.}) 6. Nc3 d6 7. d4 $1 exd4 8. Qxd4 $14 {White has all the pieces in play
and Black is in some serious trouble.}) (4... d6 $5 {After this move, the play
will be very similar to the classical d3 spanish.} 5. c3 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1
Bd7 8. Nbd2 Re8 9. Ba4 $5 $14 {The play follows as in typical spanish lines we
will discover in next lectures.} Bf8 10. Bc2 g6 11. b4 Bg7 12. a4 $14 {White
has good queenside play.}) 5. O-O $1 {with a very nice idea in mind.} Nd4 $1 {
by far the most common move and the reason why 5.0-0 is not the most common
move, but an unpleasant surprise is waiting for Black!} (5... d6 6. Nc3 $1 {
this is the best here, and White easily gets a small advantage!} O-O (6... a6 {
It seldom makes sense to allow this doubled pawns.} 7. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 8. d4 exd4
9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nf3 $3 {We now wish to play for e5 to weaken those doubled
pawns.} O-O 11. e5 $1 dxe5 12. Nxe5 $14 Re8 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 15. Bf4
Bd6 16. Bg3 $14 {with a risk free endgame advantage}) (6... Bd7 7. Na4 $1 Bb6
8. Nxb6 axb6 9. a4 $1 $14 {supporting the Bishop.}) 7. Na4 Bb6 (7... Nd4 8.
Nxc5 $1 Nxb5 9. a4 $3 dxc5 (9... Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Nb3 c5 12. Bg5 $16 {
The g5-d8 pin is super annoying for Black to handle. There can be threats like
Qf3-Bf6 or f4-e5.}) 10. axb5 Qd6 11. Bd2 $14 {Black is stuck defending his
weak pawns, while White can slowly improve and hit on them.} Bd7 12. Bc3 Rfe8
13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. f4 Ree8 15. e5 $16 {wins material.}) 8. Nxb6 axb6 9. h3 $14 {
stopping Bg4, White's play flows for itself.}) 6. Be3 $1 {A very intresting
and rare line, after this move we manage to get a small advantage (or a big
one! ) in a position with several possibilities ! Thats the best deal for
white against the Berlin Spanish.} Nxf3+ {this should be the best.} (6... c6 $5
{is playable.} 7. Bxd4 (7. Ba4 $1 {this quite move will take us to playable
and interesting positions.} d6 (7... Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 O-O 10. Bb3 $1
{transposes to the main lines.}) 8. Bxd4 $1 (8. Nxd4 $5 {The other option,
which is also possible.} exd4 (8... Bxd4 $6 9. Bxd4 exd4 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nd2
$14 {typical play!}) 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 $1 (10. Bh4 $4 g5 11. Bg3 h5 $17 {
be aware of these nasty tricks. Black suddlenly has an upper hand because of
your dumb Bishop.}) 10... Qxf6 11. f4 $14 {White is doing good.}) 8... exd4 9.
Nbd2 a5 (9... O-O 10. Nb3 b5 11. Nxc5 dxc5 12. Bb3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 {
unclear.}) 10. c3 dxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. d4 Ba7 13. Bb3 $14 {White has a stable
posiiton.}) 7... exd4 8. e5 $1 Nd5 (8... cxb5 $2 {Black goes for material but
the problem is it weakens his own King.} 9. exf6 Qxf6 10. Re1+ Kd8 11. Nbd2 $16
{White is better developed and has good control of the position.}) (8... Nh5 {
cheaky stuff.} 9. Bc4 O-O 10. Nbd2 d5 11. exd6 Nf4 (11... Bxd6 {We are not
forced to get into this troublesome complications, but it still favors us.} 12.
Nxd4 Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qxd4 14. Qxh5 Qf4+ 15. Kg1 Qxd2 16. Rae1 Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6
18. Re2 Qb4 19. Qe5 $16 {White has a clearly better position because of his
pawn structure.}) 12. Ne4 Bxd6 13. Nxd4 $3 Be5 14. Nf3 Bxb2 15. Rb1 Bf6 16. a4
$1 {Once again, a4 seems to be the best move.}) 9. Bc4 Nb6 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nbd2
d5 12. exd6 $1 Bxd6 13. Re1 Bg4 $2 14. Re4 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 c5 16. Nd2 Qc7 17. g3
$16 {White has a strong kingside.}) (6... O-O $6 {a weak move} 7. Nxd4 $1 exd4
(7... Bxd4 8. Bxd4 exd4 9. e5 $14 {White is much better due to doubled pawns
and active pieces.}) 8. Bg5 $1 {threatening e5.} h6 (8... c6 9. Bc4 Be7 {
Black wants to play for d5.} 10. Nd2 h6 (10... d5 11. exd5 cxd5 12. Bb3 {
White has better pawn structure which is a big advantage for the endgame.}) 11.
Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Bb3 d6 13. Qh5 {planning f4-e5.} a5 14. a4 Bd7 (14... Be6 15.
Bxe6 fxe6 16. f4 {White has good control of the center.}) 15. f4 {intending a
possible e5 in future.}) (8... Be7 {Black is planning c6-d5.} 9. Nd2 $1 c6 10.
Bc4 d5 (10... d6 11. a4 $16 {always take space and stop b5.}) 11. exd5 Nxd5 12.
Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Re1 $16 {White has good space.}) 9. Bxf6 (9. Bh4 $5 {This is
also possible, keeping the annoying pawn.} c6 10. Ba4 Be7 11. Bxf6 $3 {
brilliant! We capture now to to misplace, Black's dark squared Bishop.}) 9...
Qxf6 10. Nd2 c6 11. Bc4 d6 12. f4 $14 {White is better.}) 7. Qxf3 Bxe3 (7...
Qe7 $6 8. Nd2 $1 O-O 9. Bc4 {with typical play and a nice small advantage for
White! Theory is not important in these lines.} c6 (9... Bxe3 10. Qxe3 d6 11.
f4 $5 $14 {followed by standard moves like a4, a5, Nf3.}) (9... d6 $2 {
completely stupid.} 10. Bxc5 $1 $16 dxc5 11. a4 $1 $14 {White is clearly
better. There was no reason for Black to double his pawns like that.}) 10. a4
Bxe3 (10... d5 {central break, but it breaks black.} 11. Bb3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 dxe4
13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 $16 {Black should have kept his Rook on e8 before
trying for central breaks like these.}) 11. Qxe3 {The queen works like a
maestro here.} d5 12. Bb3 dxe4 (12... Bd7 {Black hopes to protect the e5-pawn.}
13. exd5 cxd5 14. Rae1 Rae8 15. d4 $14 {typical way to expose, Black's bad
pawn center.}) 13. Nxe4 Bf5 (13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Bd7 15. Rae1 Rae8 16. d4 {
wins material.}) 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Rae1 Rfe8 16. d4 $16 Qg6 17. Re2 e4 18. f3
{Once again, we somehow always win a pawn when Black places his queen on e7
and follows up with d5.}) (7... Bb6 $2 {Black gets tactical problems.} 8. Bxb6
axb6 9. d4 Qe7 (9... exd4 10. e5 Ng8 11. Qg4 g6 12. Qxd4 $18 {Black is done
for real.}) 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Nc3 O-O 12. a4 $16 {White has good control.}) 8.
Qxe3 $1 {Our queen stands perfectly on e3, controlling many important squares.}
c6 (8... O-O 9. Bc4 $1 {The most accurate but everything else is playable too.}
d6 (9... c6 10. Bb3 {transposes to the main line.}) (9... Re8 10. f4 exf4 (
10... d6 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Nd2 Be6 13. a4 $16 {The control of the open f-file
and space on queenside matters.}) 11. Qxf4 (11. Rxf4 $4 d5 $17 {shouldn't have
been allowed.}) 11... d6 12. Nd2 c6 13. Kh1 $14 d5 14. Bb3 Be6 15. e5 Nd7 16.
Rae1 $1 $14 {White has space advantage and next plan is probably something
like c3-d4-Bc2 with checkmate on the kingside.}) 10. Nd2 c6 (10... a5 11. a4 $1
{Always go a4, after a5.} c6 12. Bb3 $14 {again, plans matter here.}) 11. Bb3 {
once again arriving in the main line} Re8 12. f4 $14 Be6 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Bxe6
Rxe6 15. a4 $14 {with good play.}) 9. Bc4 $1 O-O (9... d6 $5 10. Nd2 (10. Bb3
$5 {The typical retreat. We don't to face tempos.} Qb6 11. Qd2 $5 O-O 12. a4 a5
13. Na3 $14 {which is also playable but not very typical.}) 10... Qb6 (10...
O-O 11. Bb3 $14 {a4 is also good enough.}) 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. a4 {with a slow
endgame.}) (9... Qb6 $2 10. Qg5 $16 {wins material in a complex line ahead.})
10. Bb3 $1 {This is the basic position of the Berlin with d3-Be3! Its a big
battlefield with many possible ideas for both sides and very interesting play
for White. Our main idea is Bb3-Nd2 and f4! intending fe5! and whenever Black
goes a5...we go a4!} d6 (10... Re8 {Black can be allowed to play Qe7-d5?!
since these 2 moves do not go well together, but he should not be allowed to
play Re8-c6-d5, for this reason after Re8 we go f4!} 11. f4 $1 $14 d6 $6 (11...
exf4 12. Qxf4 d6 13. Nd2 $14 {White can play on the kingside without any
problems.}) (11... d5 $6 {This breaks unfortunately doesn't work for Black.}
12. fxe5 Rxe5 13. Qg3 $3 Re8 14. exd5 $1 cxd5 15. Nc3 $1 $14 Be6 {And now
comes the classic manuever.} 16. Qf2 $3 a6 17. Qd4 $1 $14 {Suddenly, White
controls the position more then anything.}) 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Nd2 $16 {This is
a bad structure for Black, White is better.} (13. Kh1) 13... Be6 (13... Qb6 $2
{Black is trying to trade, but who will tell him the endgame is worse not just
because there is a concrete tactic.} 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Nc4 $18 (15. a4 $16 {
Even here White is completely better.}) 15... b5 16. Nd6 Re7 17. Nxf7 Rxf7 18.
d4 $18 exd4 19. Bxf7+ (19. e5 Nd5 {dont be a fool.}) 19... Kxf7 20. e5 {
winning material.}) 14. Bxe6 $1 Rxe6 15. a4 $16 {These positions are always
slightly better for White. He can create little threats on the kingside by
moves like Qg3/g5-Nc4-Ne3-Nf5 and/or play moves like a5 and at some point
expand on the queenside.}) (10... Qb6 $6 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Nd2 $14 {Black has
some weaknesses.}) (10... Qe7 {Black can be allowed to play Qe7-d5, as this is
usually not that good.} 11. Nd2 d5 $2 {The problem is, his e5-pawn will be too
weak.} (11... d6 12. f4 a5 13. a4 $14 {with standard play.}) 12. exd5 $1 $16
cxd5 (12... Nxd5 13. Qg3 $16 f6 14. Rae1 Kh8 15. d4 $18 {The pressure on the
e5-pawn, decided the game as you can see.}) 13. Rae1 $16 {with a good position.
}) (10... a5 11. a4 $1 {Note! We always play a4 in response of ...a5 by Black.
Don't allow him to extend on the queenside.} Re8 12. f4 $1 {Remmember to
always meet Re8 with f4!} exf4 13. Qxf4 d6 14. Nd2 $16 {with typical moves
like Kh1-h3.}) 11. Nd2 $1 {And here are some, sample lines once again! Just to
get a good feeling of the resulting middlegame positions!} a5 (11... Qe7 12. f4
$1 $14 Be6 13. fxe5 $1 dxe5 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 15. Qf3 $1 $14 {Our plan is simple,
a4 to avoid ...b5 and next Nc4-Ne3-Kh1 and}) (11... Re8 12. f4 $1 $14 a5 13.
fxe5 dxe5 14. a4 $14 {These positions are always slightly better for White. He
can create little threats on the kingside by moves like Qg3/g5-Nc4-Ne3-Nf5.}) (
11... Be6 $6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. c3 Qe7 14. a4 a5 15. Nc4 $14 {A good version of
the Italian.}) (11... Qc7 $6 12. f4 $14 {followed by some ideas like fe5-Rf6.})
(11... Qb6 $4 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. Nc4 $18 {winning a pawn.}) (11... Nh5 $2 12. a4
Nf4 13. g3 $1 $16 Ng6 14. f4 $16 {Black lost important time by manuevering and
didnt achieve much either.}) 12. a4 $1 Be6 (12... Re8 13. f4 Be6 14. fxe5 $1
dxe5 15. Bxe6 Rxe6 16. h3 $14 {Alternatives are also possible. Plans matter
here more then any concrete theory.} (16. Kh1 $14) (16. Qf2 $14)) 13. Bxe6 fxe6
14. c3 $14 Qe7 15. Nc4 $14 {White has a good version of the italian} *

