49,28,35,19,43,14,16,22,17,54,42,15,61,58,70,16,53,42,51,51,51,22,74,57,118,77,
54,65,95,81,85,90,74,66,83,97,80,78,86,86,109,49,94]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O Nd4 6. Be3 Nxf3+ (6... O-O $6 {A little dubious.} 7.
Nxd4 exd4 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nd2 c6 10. Bc4 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Qf3
$16 {White has good position.}) 7. Qxf3 Bxe3 (7... Qe7 8. Nd2 O-O 9. Bc4 {
Again we always retreat with Bc4-Bb3, not allowing them by tempos.} c6 10. Bb3
d6 $2 (10... Bxe3 11. Qxe3 d5 12. exd5 {The pressure on the e5-pawn will
matter.}) 11. Bxc5 dxc5 12. a4 {Black invited trouble for himself by doubling
those pawns.}) 8. Qxe3 O-O 9. Bc4 c6 10. Bb3 Re8 (10... Qe7 11. Nd2 d5 12. Rae1
d4 13. Qg5 a5 14. a4 {followed by f4, White is good.}) 11. f4 $1 d6 12. Nd2 (
12. fxe5 $1 dxe5 13. Nd2 $16 {these positions are better than they look.}) (12.
f5 {is also possible but not the most optimal.} Qb6 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Nd2 d5
15. a4 {Black has some weaknesses.}) 12... Be6 13. Kh1 h6 14. Rae1 (14. fxe5 $1
dxe5 15. Qg3 Nd7 16. Nc4 $16 Qc7 17. Ne3 $1 $16 {followed by Nf5 and little
threats on the kingside.}) 14... b6 15. Nf3 Rc8 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Nh4 Bxb3 18.
axb3 Re6 19. Nf5 c5 20. Rf3 Ne8 21. Ref1 Rcc6 22. Qf2 Rf6 23. h3 Kh7 24. Qg3 g6
25. Ne3 Rxf3 26. Rxf3 f6 27. Qh4 Rd6 28. Ng4 h5 29. Ne3 Ng7 30. g4 g5 31. Qf2
h4 32. Nd5 Kg6 33. c4 a5 1/2-1/2

