Bxd4 exd4 8. e5 Nd5 9. Bc4 Nb6 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nbd2 d5 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Re1 {
This seemingly scary position for White, is actually comfortable for White.
Remember the rule, pair Bishops are only dangerous if your only Bishop is
worse.}) 7. Qxf3 Bxe3 8. Qxe3 c6 9. Bc4 O-O 10. Bb3 d6 11. Nd2 Qe7 12. f4 Be6
13. Rae1 (13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 15. a4 {White can create little threats
on the kingside by moves like Qg3/g5-Nc4-Ne3-Nf5 and play moves like a5 and at
some point expand on the queenside.}) 13... exf4 14. Rxf4 Bxb3 15. Nxb3 Rae8
16. Qf2 d5 17. e5 Nd7 18. d4 Qe6 19. Nc1 f6 20. Nd3 fxe5 21. Nxe5 Rxf4 22. Qxf4
