{In this lecture, we are going to see 5.d3 lines in Spanish.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 {Please don't confuse yourself, with this
position and the text line. They are both completely different and don't
transpose into each other.}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 {The start of the 5.d3 variation.
This line helps you save on a lot of theory of the mainline Spanish and also
creates enough challenges for your opponent, that every level can play this.} (
5. O-O {We can also delay playing d3 and play this variation, however, should
also know theory here, which is the Open Spanish.} Nxe4) 5... d6 (5... b5 6.
Bb3 Bc5 7. c3 {This will be examined separately in the next lecture.}) 6. c3 {
White now has two main options, either play g6-Bg7 or Be7-0-0. White plans to
castle short, play useful waiting moves like Re1/h3 and then further decide
how to develop based on Black's play. Our play is mostly focused on the
queenside with moves like b4-a4, in the future.} *

