{[%evp 0,27,16,28,18,25,39,-9,12,-22,3,3,-2,-20,7,-6,1,-22,-4,-13,3,9,0,0,12,
12,30,1,32,32]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 $1 {This is a
very interesting move! Black has several different set-ups but in most cases
we will avoid all the theory and keep the typcal plans of the Spanish. In
general, our play is focused on the queenside. We pick one of the set ups and
try to go a4/b4.} d6 $5 (5... Be7 {looses the e5-pawn.} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 {
White is a pawn up.}) (5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 (6... Bc5 $1 7. c3 {will be examined
seperately under the d3-Bc5 set-ups !}) 7. O-O Be7 8. c4 $1 {will transpose to
the Old Archangelsk with the early Bb7 move, examined under the 4th move
alternatives}) 6. c3 $1 {Black has a couple of options now, either to play
Be7-0-0 or g6-Bg7-0-0.} (6. O-O $2 {is a mistake.} b5 $1 7. Bb3 Na5 $15 {
You can't just giveaway your spanish Bishop like this.}) 6... g6 $1 {playing
g6 against slow play with c3-d3 is a very interesting idea, but White also has
some ideas in mind.} (6... Be7 $5 {simple developing move.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
Re8 9. Nbd2 {with typical Spanish play!} (9. h3 $1 {It is also possible to
throw on this waiting move, to check Black's cards.} Bf8 (9... h6 10. Nbd2 Bf8
11. Nf1 b5 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. Ne3 g6 14. a4 $14 {with a slightly different set-up
but still good play on the queenside!}) 10. Bg5 $1 h6 11. Bh4 g6 12. Nbd2 Bg7
13. b4 $1 $14 {White has good prospective play on the queenside. Black has
wasted too much time by going Be7-Bf8-Bg7 when he could have played g6-Bg7 in
the first place.}) 9... Bf8 10. Nf1 g6 (10... h6 11. Ng3 g6 12. h3 Bg7 13. Bd2
$14 Bd7 14. b4 $1 {White has good play on the queenside.}) 11. Bg5 $1 h6 12.
Bh4 Bg7 13. Ne3 b5 14. Bc2 $14 {Again, this is better version of g6-Bg7 lines,
instead of Be7-g6-Bf8-Bg7.}) (6... Bd7 $5 {This move won't change any of our
plans. Black will soon continue either with g6 or Be7. Just be aware of some
tricks on e8-a4 diagonal after Black plays Qe8. You will understand in a
moment.} 7. O-O Be7 (7... g6 8. Re1 Bg7 9. h3 {We are waiting but Bg5 right
now is also possible.} O-O 10. Bg5 $1 Qe8 {Black can have some Nd4 threats in
the future but not right now as we can simply take the Knight and play b3.
White's plan is something like Nd2-b4-Bc2.}) 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. Nbd2 Bf8
11. Nf1 g6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Bg7 14. Ne3 Ne7 15. Bc2 g5 16. Bg3 Ng6 17. a4 $14
{This is quite a battle here.}) 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 $1 {A useful waiting move,
we will decide our setup soon.} O-O 9. h3 $1 {This is also very interesting,
intending Be3 or Bg5 in the next few moves! In general h3 is a useful waiting
move. Once again, knowledge of plans is more important then memorisation.} (9.
Bg5 $1 h6 10. Bh4 {our plan is usually to play on the queenside with moves
like Nbd2-b4! -Bb3 etc etc ...if black plays b7-b5 we usually go Bc2!} Re8 (
10... b5 {Black tries to develop his Bishop from b7.} 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. Nbd2 Re8
13. a4 Qd7 14. b4 $14 {with typical slight edge.}) 11. Nbd2 b5 (11... Bd7 $5 {
Of course several moves are possible, don't memorize anything, just understand.
} 12. Nf1 $1 {The alternatives are possible as well.} (12. Bc2 $5 b5 13. a4 Rb8
14. b4 $14 {with a rich middlegame ahead.}) (12. b4 $5 {gaining space on the
queenside.} b5 13. Bb3 a5 14. a3 $14 {White is stable.}) 12... Ne7 13. Bc2 c5
14. a4 b5 15. Ne3 $14 {with slow play ahead.}) 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. a4 (13. d4 $6 {
Be careful when you play d3-d4, because it will activate, Black's forces as
well! Usually when Black abandons the center with Nh5 intending f7-f5, then we
go d3-d4.} exd4 14. cxd4 g5 15. Bg3 g4 16. Nh4 Nxd4 {As we can see it turned
out against.}) 13... Nb8 {Black is planning c5-Nd7, typical Spanish manuever.}
(13... b4 $6 14. a5 $16 {fixing the a6-pawn.}) 14. b4 Nbd7 15. Nb3 $14) 9...
Bd7 (9... Re8 10. Be3 $1 (10. Bg5 $1 {is also possible and would transpose.})
10... b5 (10... h6 11. Nbd2 Nh5 12. d4 $1 $14 {Remember this plan! When Black
goes Nh5-f5, we go d3-d4.} b5 13. Bc2 exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 c5 16. Qc1 Bb7
17. a3 Nc6 18. d5 Na5 19. Bd3 {followed by a4. White has amazing grip over
this position.}) 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. Nbd2 Nb8 13. b4 $1 Nbd7 14. Nb3 Rb8 15. a4 $14
) (9... Nb8 $5 {was the choice of Magnus Carlsen ! ..and in my view ..after
that the best move is ...Bc2! followed by a fast a2-a4!} 10. Bc2 $1 Nbd7 11. a4
b6 12. Bg5 $14 (12. d4 $14) 12... Bb7 13. d4 $1 h6 14. Bh4 Qe8 15. Nbd2) 10.
Be3 $5 (10. Bg5 $5 {transposes into something we have seen before.}) 10... Re8
(10... Qe8 11. Nbd2 Kh8 12. Bb3 $1 {sidestepping Nd4 tricks.} (12. d4 $4 Nxd4 {
thats the idea of the Bd7-Qe8 plan, so be careful!}) 12... Nh5 13. d4 $3 $14 {
Brilliant! Don't wait for them to play f5, take twice, Qg6. Our aim as you
probably understood is to open the center.} f5 $2 14. dxe5 {Black played for a
flank attack without a blocked center...so now White opens up the position and
Black is just collecting weaknesses!} dxe5 (14... f4 15. Bd4 dxe5 16. Bc5 Rf6
17. Bd5 $16) 15. Bc5 $16 {Black has some noticable targets.}) 11. Nbd2 b5 12.
Bc2 $14 h6 13. a4 Rb8 (13... d5 $2 {black forgot about his c5 square !!} 14.
Nb3 $16) 14. b4 $14 {White has that typical Spanish edge.} *

