{In this lecture we are going to see b5/Bc5 lines in the 5.d3 variation.} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bb3 {If the Bishop
was on e7, we would have retreated back to c2 but as Na5 plans are not
effective here, we can keep our Bishop on the long diagonal.} d6 8. Bg5 {
This is the main tabia of this variation. Our play is based on plans and not
concrete theory. White wants to basically annoy Black with the g5-d8 diagonal
pin.If Black in response plays h6-g5, we go with d4 to open up the position.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "Saint Louis USA"]
[Date "2025.01.21"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.d3 Part 2 - Bc5 lines"]
[Black "Theory/plans"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C77"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[EventDate "2023.03.19"]
[EventType "k.o."]
[SourceVersionDate "2017.10.16"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 {This is one of the main
replies to the 5.d3 variation. As you will often see in this variation, our
plan is 0-0, a4 followed by Na3 and also keeping the d3-d4 advance in mind,
especially if Black tries h6-g5. Do note, that concrete theory is not
important at all, as Black has several setups and White has many move orders.}
6. c3 $1 b5 (6... O-O $5 {Black simply castles. The idea is to meet Bc6 with
bc6 and Ne5 with d5, with some counterplay. But ofc we don't want to go there.}
7. Bg5 h6 (7... b5 8. Bb3 Be7 9. O-O d6 10. Nbd2 {White has a better version
of d3-Be7 lines as Black wasted on tempo.}) 8. Bh4 Be7 9. Bg3 $1 d6 10. Nbd2
Bd7 11. O-O $14 Nh5 12. Re1 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bf6 14. Nf1 $14 {Black has two
Bishops but one of them is too bad. White still has a small edge.}) 7. Bb3 $1 {
If Black had his bishop on e7, we would have played Bc2! However, with his
Bishop on c5, we can keep our Bishop on b3 as Na5 plans are not effective.} d6
(7... Na5 8. Bc2 {Black has to take care of b4 threats.}) (7... h6 {Just to
indicate our plan} 8. d4 $16 exd4 9. e5 $18 {White has huge central control
and is winning.}) (7... O-O 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 {Don't be afraid to keep your
Bishop seemingly locked there. In fact, its Black who has to worry of that pin.
} Be7 10. Bg3 d6 11. h3 {White is stable.}) 8. Bg5 $1 {This move is a big part
of our plan. Black cannot get rid of the pin and he needs to play g7-g5 which
may offer some initiative, but it is also very weak, especially if White
manages to coordinate his play in the center with d4.} h6 (8... Rb8 9. O-O h6
10. Bh4 {with typical play.}) 9. Bh4 {There is no concrete play in this line.
Given are some sample continuations} Bd7 (9... Na5 10. Bc2 {Black has to again
move the Knight to stop b4. So it doesn't make sense to combine Bc5 and Na5.})
(9... O-O 10. O-O (10. a4 b4 11. a5 Rb8 {is also possible.}) 10... Bb6 (10...
Bg4 11. Nbd2 {There is hardly any point for Black to try Bg4 as we can defend
with Nd2.}) 11. a4 $1 {Our main plan is a4-Na3 to generate counterplay on the
queenside.} Rb8 12. axb5 axb5 13. Na3 $1 b4 $2 (13... Na5 $1 14. Ba2 $14 {
White is better.}) (13... Bd7 {falls a pawn to} 14. Nxb5 $1 Bxf2+ $2 15. Rxf2
Rxb5 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd4 {tricky trick to win material.}) 14. Nc4 $16 {
White has good piece coordination and he controls both the wings.}) (9... g5 {
quite a bold move, as once we open the center it will get super risky for
Black.} 10. Bg3 Qe7 (10... Nh5 11. Bd5 {pinning the Knight.} Bd7 12. d4 $14
exd4 13. Nxd4 $1 $16 {White is clearly better.}) (10... O-O 11. Nbd2 Kg7 12.
O-O $1 {We simply prepare for d4 slowly.} Be6 (12... Nh7 $4 13. Bd5 Bd7 14. d4
$18 {Black can't leave controling the center.}) (12... a5 $2 13. a4 b4 14. Nc4
$16 {White has a positional advantage.}) 13. Re1 $1 Bxb3 14. Nxb3 $1 Bb6 15. d4
Re8 16. Qc2 $16 {Slowly but surely the weaknesses will speak.}) 11. O-O $1 Bb7
$2 12. a4 O-O 13. Re1 Ba7 14. Na3 $3 $16 {1-0 (44) Prag,R-Mikaelyan,A/
Tsaghkadzor ARM 2021/ Once again this typical way to create counterplay on the
queenside.}) (9... Bb6 {Black doesn't want to catch d4 with a tempo.} 10. a4
Rb8 11. axb5 axb5 12. O-O g5 13. Bg3 Ne7 14. Na3 $1 c6 15. Re1 O-O 16. d4 $16
Ng6 17. Nc2 $16 {White will slowly transfer his Knight on f5 and double up on
a-file or d-file.}) (9... Bg4 10. Nbd2 Bb6 11. h3 Bd7 12. Nf1 $14 {Black just
wasted his own time by Bg4-Bd7.}) 10. O-O $1 Qe7 (10... Bb6 11. a4 Rb8 12. axb5
axb5 13. Na3 $3 $14 {Once again our typical plan shows up.}) (10... O-O 11. d4
$1 $16 {We always love to get d4 with a tempo, even better the d7-Bishop is
hanging.} Bb6 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bxf6 {winning material.}) (10... g5 11. Bg3 Nh5
(11... h5 12. h4 g4 13. Ng5 {Black has only one plan now, Ng8-f6 to kick the
g5-Knight but I don't think it's possible.}) 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 {As the
position opens up, Black's King will face the pressure.}) 11. a4 Rb8 12. axb5
axb5 13. Re1 O-O (13... g5 14. Bg3 Bb6 (14... O-O 15. d4 Bb6 16. Na3 $16 {
with typical play.}) 15. Na3 $1 $16 {a rich middlegame ahead.}) 14. d4 $16 {
White has better pieces and Black needs to do something of the annoying pin.} *

