{This is a model game for White in the fast 0-0, Re1 and a4-Na3.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bb3 $1 d6 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4
Bd7 10. O-O Bb6 (10... O-O 11. d4 $3 $16 Bb6 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bxf6 {We have
seen this tactic before as well.}) 11. a4 Rb8 (11... O-O $2 {Black is missing
something.} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nh4 {White is
clearly better.}) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Na3 $3 $14 g5 (13... O-O 14. Nxb5 Bxf2+ (
14... Na5 15. Ba4 {supporting the Knight, White is okay tactically.}) 15. Rxf2
Rxb5 16. Bd5 {Black has huge porblems deadling with the annoying pin.}) 14. Bg3
Ne7 15. d4 $18 (15. Re1 {is also possible but little slower.} O-O 16. d4 exd4
17. Nxd4 {which is still better for White but Black's King has escaped for now.
}) 15... exd4 16. e5 $18 {boom! The standard way to attack the King.} (16. Re1
$16 dxc3 17. bxc3 {Engines like this as well.}) 16... dxe5 17. Nxe5 O-O 18.
cxd4 (18. Qf3 $1 Kg7 19. Rad1 $16 {White is doing complete dominance.}) 18...
Nf5 19. Nc2 Kg7 20. Qf3 $3 $16 Nxd4 21. Nxd4 Bxd4 22. Rad1 c5 23. Nxd7 Qxd7 24.
Bxb8 Rxb8 25. Bc2 Qd5 26. Qg3 Re8 27. b3 Nh5 28. Qg4 Nf4 29. h4 Re2 30. hxg5
hxg5 31. Bd3 Rb2 32. Bxb5 Rxb3 33. Ba6 Kg6 0-1

