1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. Bg5 h6
9. Bh4 Ba7 10. Nbd2 g5 11. Bg3 Qe7 12. Nf1 (12. a4 $1 {This waiting move is
better as it doesn't reveal our hand yet.}) 12... Be6 13. Ne3 Rb8 (13... Bxe3
14. fxe3 {White has no problems. The doubled pawns actually help in
controlling the central squares.}) 14. O-O Bxe3 15. fxe3 $14 O-O 16. Nd2 Bg4 (
16... Kh7 17. d4 $16 {White's aim in these kind of structures is always to
play d4 with support on e4.}) 17. Qe1 Bh5 18. Nf3 Kg7 19. Nh4 Bg6 20. Nf5+ Bxf5
21. Rxf5 Nd7 22. Qe2 Qe8 23. Raf1 f6 24. h4 Ne7 25. R5f2 Nc5 26. Bc2 Ng6 27. h5
Ne7 28. d4 Nd7 29. Bb3 Rd8 30. a4 f5 31. dxe5 Nxe5 32. exf5 Kf6 33. Be6 Qc6 34.
axb5 Qxb5 35. Qd1 a5 36. b3 Rb8 37. Ra2 N7c6 38. e4 Qc5+ 39. Bf2 Qxc3 40. Rc2
Qb4 41. Bd5 Ne7 42. Rxc7 Rfc8 43. Ra7 Rc3 44. Bc4 Rb6 45. Bd4 Rxc4 46. bxc4
N7c6 47. Rh7 1-0

